<HEAD>Piedmont Pilot Says Not a Hero For Landing Crippled Plane</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS two grafs with report right landing gear might have been
obstructed also.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREENSBORO, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The pilot who brought a crippled <ORGANIZATION> Piedmont </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> jet to a safe landing with one engine cowl scraping the ground said Thursday he's tried since to think of a better way of bringing in the plane. `` I landed that aircraft probably a thousand times last night to see if I could have done any better _ and I could n't,'' pilot <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Fuda </PERSON> said during a news conference Thursday at <LOCATION> Piedmont </LOCATION> Triad International Airport. Flight 1489 originated at <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> <LOCATION> National </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> and was bound for <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> S.C. </LOCATION>, with a stop in <LOCATION> Charlotte </LOCATION>. It was diverted to <LOCATION> Greensboro </LOCATION> when the crew could n't get the left landing gear down. <PERSON> Fuda </PERSON> said he decided to go to <LOCATION> Greensboro </LOCATION> to avoid the more congested Charlotte-Douglas International Airport. <PERSON> Fuda </PERSON> said he liked the emergency equipment at <LOCATION> Greensboro </LOCATION> and knew <LOCATION> Greensboro </LOCATION>'s runway was as long as <LOCATION> Charlotte </LOCATION>'s He also knew a large contingent of <LOCATION> Piedmont </LOCATION> people were close by. <PERSON> Fuda </PERSON> set the <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 737-400 down on its right and nose landing gear, then settled the plane onto its left engine and skidded to a halt on the 10,000-foot runway, a shower of sparks coming from the dragging metal. `` I hardly knew that the wheel was n't there when we touched down,'' <PERSON> Fuda </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Fuda </PERSON> said he had no previous experience like Wednesday's in his 21 years of flying for <LOCATION> Piedmont </LOCATION>. `` I always wondered what I would do if it did happen,'' he said. Passengers aboard <LOCATION> Piedmont </LOCATION> Flight 1489, which made the landing at <LOCATION> Piedmont </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Triad </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>, said later they thought Fuda was a hero. `` There was no hysteria,'' said <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Kochan </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, a lobbyist who says he flies a lot. `` But there were a lot of trips to the bathroom.'' <PERSON> Fuda </PERSON>'s wife, <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON>, said her husband does n't think of himself as a hero. `` He's just glad it worked out,'' she said. `` The whole crew did just what they were supposed to do. He says he does n't consider himself a hero.'' `` This time it worked out the way it was supposed to work. Sometimes the crew does the right things and things do n't work out as well,'' she said. `` He's pooped. I've been giving him kisses and hugs since he got home.'' Fuda was not originally scheduled to pilot Flight 1489, said his neighbor <PERSON> Donnie </PERSON> <PERSON> Campbell </PERSON>, a retired <LOCATION> Piedmont </LOCATION> pilot. `` He was supposed to work Friday night, but they're having a ` Farewell to <LOCATION> Piedmont </LOCATION>' party in <LOCATION> Roanoke </LOCATION> -LRB- <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION> -RRB- Friday night, and he wanted to go to that. So he just picked up a flight that somebody dropped.'' `` I'm waiting to see the pilot I picked it up from,'' <PERSON> Fuda </PERSON> said. The party is to celebrate Piedmo n't final flight on Saturday before its merger with <ORGANIZATION> USAir </ORGANIZATION> is completed _ to which <PERSON> Fuda </PERSON> made jocular reference: `` I have made my last and best landing for <LOCATION> Piedmont </LOCATION>,'' he said. The 94 passengers and six crew members safely jumped down emergency chutes. A rubber wheel chock found wedged in the wheel well had prevented the left main landing gear from deploying, said the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> Piedmont </LOCATION> spokesman <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Shipley </PERSON> said Thursday it would be mere speculation to suggest that the chock, a triangular rubber block 30 inches long and 6 inches high used to keep planes from rolling when they're parked, was left in the wheel well at <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> National. `` There's really nothing else to say,'' <PERSON> Shipley </PERSON> added. `` The airplane's in the hangar, and we estimate it to be in service Saturday.'' Only the left engine housing was damaged during the landing, <PERSON> Shipley </PERSON> said. The 11-month-old plane's left wing and skin were unharmed. The plane's engine housing is designed to hold up during that type of emergency landing, he said. `` Apparently, -LRB- the wing -RRB- never touched the ground,'' he said. `` The engine itself is apparently undamaged, but we will remove it and replace it and run it through a complete structural check as well.'' <PERSON> Phillip </PERSON> <PERSON> Powell </PERSON>, an <ORGANIZATION> NTSB </ORGANIZATION> air safety investigator, said investigators found the chock wedged between two wheels on the left landing gear. While airline officials doubt the chock was deliberately placed, they declined to rule out any possibility pending further investigation, <PERSON> Shipley </PERSON> said. The <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> in Friday editions quoted <PERSON> Powell </PERSON> as saying the right landing gear might also have been obstructed. Two bent hydraulic lines were found in the right wheel well, raising the possiblity that a chock might also have been stuck in the right landing gear and fallen out, <PERSON> Powell </PERSON> said.
