<HEAD>Western Wildfires at a Glance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Fires Rdp</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Here is a state-by-state look at wildfires burning in the West: <LOCATION> IDAHO </LOCATION>: Hundreds of lightning-caused fires have joined to form huge blazes in forests in the western and central part of the state, burning 98,000 acres by Thursday. Cool, moist weather overnight helped firefighting efforts. Although warmer weather is predicted for the weekend, fire bosses say there is little chance of the lightning that sparked many of the fires 12 days earlier. <LOCATION> OREGON </LOCATION>: Fires east of the <LOCATION> Cascades </LOCATION> have burned more than 93,000 acres. About 650 soldiers from <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lewis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wash. </LOCATION>, were brought in to help fight a 13,300-acre blaze in the Monument Rock Wilderness, 70 miles southwest of <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>. A 23,300-acre fire burned on the boundary of the Eagle Cap Wildneress area northwest of <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>. <LOCATION> CALIFORNIA </LOCATION>: More than 35,000 acres have burned, and the biggest active blaze was a brushfire in the <ORGANIZATION> Cleveland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> southeast of <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. The 10,800-acre blaze was 60 percent contained, but was burning toward rough terrain three miles from the <ORGANIZATION> Palomar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Observatory </ORGANIZATION>, which houses the nation's largest optical telescope. Scientists were forced to shut down the observatory Thursday for fear that ash would damage the instrument. <LOCATION> MONTANA </LOCATION>: An 800-acre blaze in the <ORGANIZATION> Custer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> was contained, but a fire on the Crow Indian Reservation southeast of Billings quickly spread to 500 acres and threatened two mountain cabins. <LOCATION> WASHINGTON </LOCATION>: Crews were mopped up an 850-acre forest fire in the Pasayten Wilderness near the Canadian border.
