<BYLINE>By NIKOS KONSTANDARAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAMOS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Rescuers crawled on their hands and knees today to reach the site of an Olympic Airways crash, but they found no survivors from the aircraft that slammed into a mountain with 34 people aboard. The British-built Short plane crashed Thursday into 4,800-foot <LOCATION> Mount </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kerkis </LOCATION> on Samos island. Airline officials blamed the accident on heavy fog that covered the mountain, the highest in the <LOCATION> Aegean </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION>. Rescuers searched for the flight recorders, which should contain information on the plane's equipment and any conversations involving the pilot. Transport and Communications Minister <PERSON> Nikos </PERSON> <PERSON> Gelestathis </PERSON> said the plane, which was flying to the island from <LOCATION> Salonica </LOCATION> in northern <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION>, carried 31 passengers, including an infant, and three crew members. All were Greek. Rescuers said they apparently were killed instantly when the aircraft hit the mountain. `` Unfortunately, we could do nothing, I checked every body I could find,'' said <PERSON> Emmanuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Karlas </PERSON>, a doctor from a village on this eastern <LOCATION> Aegean </LOCATION> island within sight of <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION>'s southwestern coast. The propeller-driven plane gave no sign of trouble before it disappeared from radar screens, officials said. Only a wing and twin-tail section of the aircraft was recognizable. The front disintegrated on impact and was just a black scar on the mountainside. Police could identify only four of the charred bodies. Olympic, <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION>'s national carrier, was flying in relatives to help identify victims. Helicopters could not land close to the crash site and rescuers crawled up the mountainside on hands and knees for 90 minutes in the dark. The steep terrain prevented them from carrying down the dead. `` We'll have the helicopters hoist out the human remains, `` said police officer <PERSON> Panayiotis </PERSON> <PERSON> Kourdonouris </PERSON>. Officials ruled out foul play as the cause of the crash. An Olympic official who spoke on condition of anonymity said: `` It appears that thick fog in the area at the time played the villain's role as the pilot flew blindly into the mountain.'' <PERSON> Gelestathis </PERSON> told lawmakers in Parliament today that a terrorist act was out of the question. Military teams were dispatched to the crash site after a shepherd reported seeing an explosion on the mountain. The <LOCATION> Athens </LOCATION> airport duty officer, <PERSON> Emmanuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Fragiadakis </PERSON>, said the control tower lost contact with the plane at about 4:55 p.m., an hour after it left <LOCATION> Salonika </LOCATION>. It was scheduled to land on Samos at 5:30 p.m. The plane disappeared from radar screens when it was 25 miles northwest of <LOCATION> Samos </LOCATION>. Olympic officials said the pilot, <PERSON> Petros </PERSON> <PERSON> Moutzoureas </PERSON>, was a veteran with an excellent flight record. They said the aircraft was bought in 1981 and was used for inter-island flights.
