<HEAD>Syrian-Christian Clashes in Beirut</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Syrian and <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> forces battled with howitzers, mortars and tank cannons across <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>'s dividing Green Line today. Police said two people were killed and seven wounded. The shelling kept many Moslems from attending their weekly Friday prayers. The latest casualties raised the overall toll to 516 killed and 2,183 wounded in the 20-week-old confrontation between Gen. <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>'s predominantly <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> troops and Syrian soldiers in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. `` They've started early today,'' grocer <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> <PERSON> Masoud </PERSON> said as he closed his store in west <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> and headed for a bomb shelter. `` What a life! We are living under the ground like the dead. We might as well die.'' A police spokesman, who can not be named in line with regulations, said the clash involved the <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> district of <PERSON> Ein </PERSON> <PERSON> Rummaneh </PERSON> and the adjacent Syrian-controlled Moslem neighborhood of <LOCATION> Chiyah </LOCATION>. He said the clash started with an exchange of sniper fire then developed into an artillery duel. It was not immediately clear who started the clash. Shells crashed into apartment buildings on both sides of the <ORGANIZATION> Green </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Line </ORGANIZATION>, which has divided <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> into Moslem and <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> sectors since the civil war broke out in April 1975. The two fatalities occurred in the densely populated slum of <LOCATION> Chiyah </LOCATION>, a stronghold for the Syrian-backed Shiite Moslem Amal militia. Amal did not take part in the confrontation, the spokesman said. Shell explosions echoed across <LOCATION> Chiyah </LOCATION> and residents rushed to underground bomb shelters as calls were blared from mosque minarets for noon prayers. The police spokesman said the shelling of <LOCATION> Chiyah </LOCATION> did not reach the nearby slum of <LOCATION> Bir </LOCATION> <LOCATION> el-Abed </LOCATION>, where followers of the Iranian-backed <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION>, or Party of God, attended prayers at the main mosque. Friday is the Moslem holy day. Syrian gunners deployed in <LOCATION> Chiyah </LOCATION> fired their 130mm Soviet-designed howitzers at the Christian suburb of <LOCATION> Kfarshima </LOCATION>, southeast of <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>, where <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>'s forces maintain some artillery batteries. <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>'s gunners, the spokesman said, responed by shelling <LOCATION> Chiyah </LOCATION> and the Druse suburb of <LOCATION> Choueifat </LOCATION> with 155mm U.S.-designed howitzers deployed northeast of the capital. The thuds of shell blasts resounded across the bomb-ravaged <LOCATION> Lebanese </LOCATION> capital, forcing the few businesses that opened early in the morning to close. Only 200,000 people of <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>'s original 1.5 million population still live in the city, which has been the site of ferocious shelling duels since the confrontation broke out March 8. Most of the evacuees have settled in safer areas in south <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, the eastern <LOCATION> Bekaa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> and the Christian-controlled mountain resorts northeast of <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>. The confrontation broke out over a blockade imposed by <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON> on illegal ports run by Syrian-backed militias south of <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> for denying the ailing state treasury about $ 100 million in lost customs dues annually. The Syrians and allied Moslem and leftist forces retaliated by shelling and besieging the 310-square-mile Christian enclave, home to about one million people northeast of the capital. <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>, 54, a <ORGANIZATION> Maronite </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION>, escalated the confrontation with the Syrians by declaring a `` war of liberation'' against their 40,000 troops, deployed in predominantly Moslem sections of the nation. An Arab mediation committee has failed to solve <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>'s crisis, rooted in an effort by the Moslem majority to wrest more power from Christians, who traditionally have dominated <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> The panel blamed <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> for blocking a settlement.
