<HEAD>Austria Closes Its Investigation of Bloch</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government said today it is closing its investigation of <PERSON> Felix </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bloch </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> diplomat suspected of spying for <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, after determining that `` <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>'s interests were not affected.'' However, Interior Minister <PERSON> Franz </PERSON> <PERSON> Loeschnak </PERSON> also told Austrian radio that 10 politicians have been asked about their relationship with <PERSON> Bloch </PERSON> and that their answers will be forwarded to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> for its investigation. The Austrian-born <PERSON> Bloch </PERSON> served at the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> in 1980-87 and was friends with many politicians, including Foreign Minister <PERSON> Alois </PERSON> <PERSON> Mock </PERSON>. In the radio interview, <PERSON> Loeschnak </PERSON> refused to identify the Austrian politicians asked to fill out questionnaires about their dealings with <PERSON> Bloch </PERSON>. He also said that <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION> is leaving it up to the politicians to respond at their own discretion. Some of the 10 have promised to comply, he said without identifying them. <PERSON> Loeschnak </PERSON> said police interviewed an Austrian woman with whom <PERSON> Bloch </PERSON> had an extended friendship. But their questioning yielded no evidence that the woman suspected anything about <PERSON> Bloch </PERSON>'s alleged spying activities, he said. No charges have been brought against <PERSON> Bloch </PERSON>, who has been stripped of his diplomatic passport and placed on administrative leave. He is under constant surveillance in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> by the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Bloch </PERSON>, 54, reportedly had broad contacts with Austrian politicians and officials, and he regularly attended all kinds of diplomatic and other parties while he was economics chief at the embassy in 1980-83 and then the No. 2 until his return to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> in July 1987. <PERSON> Loeschnak </PERSON> noted the American's contacts with the Austrian politicians `` have no -LRB- relevance -RRB- for <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>'s security interests.'' At a news conference July 28, <PERSON> Loeschnak </PERSON> said the suspicions against <PERSON> Bloch </PERSON> are `` the affair of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Bloch </PERSON> is the highest-ranking <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> diplomat to be investigated under suspicion of collaborating with the Soviets. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials were alerted to <PERSON> Bloch </PERSON>'s possible links with the <ORGANIZATION> KGB </ORGANIZATION> when they intercepted an international telephone call arranging a meeting in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> in May. There, <PERSON> Bloch </PERSON> was filmed exchanging briefcases with a man known as <PERSON> Pierre </PERSON>, whom the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> considers a Soviet spy. <PERSON> Bloch </PERSON> says he knows <PERSON> Pierre </PERSON> as a stamp collector.
