<HEAD>Homeland Reported Cracking Down On Dissidents, Violence In Soweto</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with crackdown on two communities resisting
incorporation into a homeland. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The black homeland of <LOCATION> Bophuthatswana </LOCATION> is intensifying its crackdown on two communities that have violently resisted incorporation into the territory, an anti-apartheid group said today. Also today, police imposed restrictions on the funeral of two slain activists in a township near <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Town </LOCATION> and reported a series of skirmishes between police and mixed-race youths. In other incidents, police said five blacks were killed in three separate clashes in <ORGANIZATION> Natal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Province </ORGANIZATION>, where supporters of militant and relatively conservative political factions have engaged in a three-year power struggle claiming hundreds of lives. <LOCATION> Bophuthatswana </LOCATION>, one of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s four nominally independent homelands, has arrested a local leader, banned anti-apartheid groups and restricted a lawyer's access to people in the communities of <LOCATION> Braklaagte </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Leeuwfontein </PERSON>. <PERSON> Lydia </PERSON> <PERSON> Kompe </PERSON>, spokeswoman for the <ORGANIZATION> Transvaal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Action </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> which is opposed to the tribal homeland system, said the <LOCATION> Bophuthatswana </LOCATION> government `` is still increasing its efforts against its opponents'' in the two communities. The two neighboring villages were incorporated into the homeland on Jan. 1 despite protests by many of the estimated 25,000 residents. The residents of <LOCATION> Braklaagte </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Leeuwfontein </PERSON> say they want to remain part of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> and fear they will be discriminated against by the <LOCATION> Bophuthatswana </LOCATION> government because of their opposition to incorporation. The homelands are not recognized by any foreign countries. Eleven people, including nine policemen, were killed July 1 when authorities sought to break up a rally in <LOCATION> Leeuwfontein </LOCATION> arranged by residents who opposed joining <LOCATION> Bophuthatswana </LOCATION>. Thirty-three people charged with involvement in the fighting were to appear in a <LOCATION> Bophuthatswana </LOCATION> court. <PERSON> Pupsey </PERSON> <PERSON> Sebogodi </PERSON>, leader of the <LOCATION> Braklaagte </LOCATION> community, has been arrested three times this year and remains in detention, said the <ORGANIZATION> Transvaal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Action </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, which was banned from <LOCATION> Bophuthatswana </LOCATION> by the homeland government. Authorities have threatened to deport the Rev. <PERSON> Eberhard </PERSON> <PERSON> Richter </PERSON>, a German citizen and <PERSON> Luthern </PERSON> missionary who has served the Braklaagte community since 1981, Ms. <PERSON> Kompe </PERSON> said. A South African lawyer representing the defendants, <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Sutherland </PERSON>, has been ordered to apply for a visa before he can return to the homeland. The homeland has few formal border posts and usually no visa is required to visit. About 2 million blacks live in <LOCATION> Bophuthatswana </LOCATION>, which consists of seven separate pieces of land scattered across north-central <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Town </LOCATION> regional police commissioner, Maj. Gen. <PERSON> Flip </PERSON> <PERSON> Fourie </PERSON>, imposed restrictions on Saturday's funeral of two mixed-race activists who died in a bomb blast last month. Police said <PERSON> Robbie </PERSON> <PERSON> Waterwitch </PERSON>, 20, and <PERSON> Coline </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>, 22, were trying to plant the bomb in a public toilet when it exploded. <PERSON>