<HEAD>House Military Spending Eliminates Funds for Two Bush Programs</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New lead and inserts 4th graf, And in, to raise veto threat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, deliberating less than an hour and ignoring talk of a possible veto, today approved a $ 286.5 billion military spending bill that makes wholesale changes in President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s defense program. By a vote of 312-105, the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> voted to adopt a spending plan that slashes nearly $ 2 billion for <ORGANIZATION> Star </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wars </ORGANIZATION> from the president's request strictly limits the B-2 stealth bomber program and makes drastic cuts in the MX and <LOCATION> Midgetman </LOCATION> nuclear missiles. Despite the unusually rapid approval of the costly bill by the Democratic-controlled <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, the ranking Republican on the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, Rep. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Dickinson </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> may veto the measure. And in advance of the vote, the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> budget office said the president's senior advisers would recommend a veto on grounds the measure `` would severely compromise the administration's objective of providing adequate defense capabilities within constrained resources. `` They have conformed,'' <PERSON> Dickinson </PERSON> said of the appropriations measure that conforms to the separate defense authorization bill the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> adopted last week. `` But that still makes it veto-bait in my opinion.'' The bill, approved as <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> rushed to complete pending business before starting a month-long recess later today, slashed $ 2 billion from classified programs that include the advanced fighter and advanced cruise missile. The money bill also incorporates the cuts the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> made in the Star Wars anti-missile program, the B-2 stealth bomber and the MX and <LOCATION> Midgetman </LOCATION> nuclear missiles in the policy-setting authorization bill. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> cut <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s request of $ 4.9 billion for Star Wars by $ 1.8 billion, imposed strict limitation on production of the radar-evading B-2, trimmed $ 502 million from the $ 1.1 billion sought for the MX rail-garrison system and eliminated all $ 100 million sought for the Midgetman. <PERSON> Dickinson </PERSON> said he hoped that when members of the the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> meet early in September to craft a final version of the bill, the `` most egregious add-ons and deletions can be modified and limited to make it acceptable to the administration.'' But he said as they stand now, he does not support the authorization and appropriations bills and would recommend that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> veto the legislation. `` I think it will be vetoed,'' <PERSON> Dickinson </PERSON> said. But Rep. <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Weiss </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.Y. </LOCATION>, complained about suggestions that <ORGANIZATION> House-Senate </ORGANIZATION> conferees will change what the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> did after the chamber `` worked its will on the defense authorization bill.'' `` That really borders on the ridiculous. The House has spoken,'' <PERSON> Weiss </PERSON> said. The bill adds $ 893 million to the administration's budget for the purchase of 24 new F-14 jet fighters and 12 EA-6B Prowlers, both manufactured by <ORGANIZATION> Grumman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aerospace </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has proposed canceling the F-14D, a carrier-based fighter plane the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> restored in its authorization bill The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> earmarked about $ 1 billion for 24 planes over two years. Rep. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Murtha </PERSON>, D-Pa., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Appropriations defense subcommittee, criticized the increasing costs of the Advanced Tactical Fighter and favored spending money on conventional projects The appropriations bill is designed to provide the money for the defense programs approved by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> last week. The measure calls for $ 286.5 billion in budget authority and $ 281.9 billion in outlays, but does n't include money for the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> and military construction. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> defense authorization bill totals $ 305 billion _ $ 295 billion for the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> and $ 10 billion for military nuclear programs handled by the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>.
