<HEAD>Report Says Police Errors Led to British Soccer Disaster</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with policeman suspended, police
comment. Pickup 7th pvs, ``The report ...'' Another version of this story
moved on sports circuits.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN MITCHELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A government report today said a `` failure of police control'' led to the deaths of 95 people who were crushed in a surging crowd at a soccer match, and it recommended new safety measures for all stadiums. The 71-page report said authorities at <LOCATION> Hillsborough </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Stadium </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Sheffield </LOCATION> did not recognize how big their job would be or know how to cope when problems developed in the opening minutes of an April 15 Football Association Cup semifinal. After the report's release, <LOCATION> Sheffield </LOCATION>'s top police officer, <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Yorkshire </ORGANIZATION> Chief Constable <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>, submitted his resignation, and <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Duckenfield </PERSON>, who was in charge of police at <LOCATION> Hillsborough </LOCATION>, was suspended pending further review. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> said he accepted `` full responsibility for police action'' which had `` unraveled like a hand-knitted rug, with terrible consequences to the families who lost loved ones.'' The report said drinking by `` an unruly minority'' of fans and `` confused and inadequate'' signs and tickets issued by the clubs aggravated the problem. But it primarily blamed senior police officials. `` Neither their handling of problems on the day nor their account of it in evidence showed the qualities of leadership expected of their rank,'' it said. `` The main reason for the disaster was the failure of police control.'' The crush occurred when fans in a standing-room section near the field were crushed against a steel fence by hundreds of people who surged into the stadium behind them. The report recommended a 15 percent reduction in standing-room sections at British soccer stadiums and better safety procedures near the steel fences designed to keep rowdy fans off the field. The report was sent for review to the Home Office, where Secretary <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> Hurd </PERSON> said officials had failed to learn from past problems, including the Heysel riots in <LOCATION> Brussels </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Bradford </LOCATION> city fire that killed more than 50 people in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>. `` The tragedy would not have occurred if lessons learned in the past had been properly applied,'' <PERSON> Hurd </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Rogan </PERSON> <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Football </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supporters </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, said he was pleased with the report but that it did not eliminate the possibility of future stadium tragedies. `` When 50,000 people gather together, there's a risk of something like this happening,'' he said. `` I think his report is trying to reduce that risk.'' A lack of advance work and inadequate communication led to a buildup of fans outside the <LOCATION> Leppings </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lane </LOCATION> entrance to the stadium, where <ORGANIZATION> Liverpool </ORGANIZATION> was playing <LOCATION> Nottingham </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Forest </LOCATION>, the report said. Once police ordered a large gate be opened to let fans in, just before kickoff, there was inadequate effort to direct them away from an already packed standing-room section. A surge of hundreds of <LOCATION> Liverpool </LOCATION> fans into the area, known as <ORGANIZATION> Pen </ORGANIZATION> 3, pushed those already there forward, crushing victims against metal fences or concrete floors and walls, it said. `` Failure to cut off access to the central pens'' was the main cause of the tragedy, Justice <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON>, who headed the inquiry, said in the report. `` They were already overfull because no safe maximum capacities had been laid down. ... When the influx entered Pen 3 the layout of the barriers afforded less protection than it should and a barrier collapsed. Again the lack of vigilant monitoring caused a sluggish reaction. `` The club and police should have realized that the turnstile area could not easily cope with the large numbers demanded of it unless they -LRB- fans -RRB- arrived steadily over a lengthy period.'' Officials said the report's recommendations should be implemented to insure safety during the new English soccer season starting Aug. 19.
