<FIRST>r i AM-Belgium-China     08-04 0243</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Belgium-China,0249</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hundreds of Chinese Turned Away in Asking Belgium for Asylum</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 About 1,000 Chinese swamped government offices for a third day in a row Friday, apparently prompted by rumors it was easy to gain asylum in <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION>, officials said. `` We do n't know who started the rumors, but there is not a grain of truth to it,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Jean-Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Raskin </PERSON>. Almost all of the Chinese have been coming from the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>, he said. Others have driven in from <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. Most work illegally in restaurants or the garment industry in those countries and have no official documents, he said. Since Wednesday, they have lined the street leading to the main refugee center in <LOCATION> Brussels </LOCATION>. They have not been deterred by official leaflets explaining the difficulties of gaining refugee status. <PERSON> Raskin </PERSON> said all requests that have been investigated during the recent surge have been turned down. Instead, the applicants have received orders to leave <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION>. `` Police have increased controls along the border,'' he said. Newspapers reported the confusion may have arisen after the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> said that following the crackdown on the pro-democracy movement in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>, Chinese already living in <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION> could ask for an extension of their residency permits. <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION> approved legislation last year to limit foreign refugees, arguing it wanted to stop those people who falsely claim to be political refugees but only come to <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION> to find work.
</TEXT>
