<SECOND>PM-Central America,0546</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sandinistas, Opposition Agree Contras Should Be Disbanded</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FILADELFO ALEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> said today the Sandinista government and opposition groups have agreed that the U.S.-supported Contra rebels should be disbanded. The government also said it would suspend the military draft for five months, starting in September, to ease tensions with the opposition and to help keep the war from flaring up. <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON>, who will attend a two-day Central American summit this weekend, said he will insist at the summit that camps housing 12,000 Contras and thousands of their dependents in southern <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> be disbanded. Honduran President <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Azcona </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoyo </PERSON> has also been saying for some time that his country finds the Contras a burden. The summit, involving the presidents of <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION>, is part of a regional peace plan that aims to negotiate an end to the Contra conflict and to the leftist guerrilla war in <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>. It is being held in the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> beach resort of <PERSON> Tela </PERSON>. The talks Saturday and Sunday will concentrate mostly on <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>. Both the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and Contra leaders are resisting the move to disband the Contras and want to postpone such a move until after <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s government holds free and fair elections Feb. 25, as promised. The agreement to back disbandment was reached after 22 hours of talks between Sandinistas and leaders of 20 opposition parties. The talks recessed Thursday night. Sandinista leaders also said they planned to suspend the military draft from September until after the February elections in an effort to ease tensions with the opposition and de-escalate the war. The talks were called by the Sandinistas to reform <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s election laws to accomodate opposition objections that their candidates were not allowed to campaign freely in past elections Past constraints on the opposition included news censorship. The agreement on disbanding the Contras `` calls on the presidents of <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> to push forward the plan to demobilize and repatriate voluntarily'' the rebels. It also called on `` the region's governments to abstain from carrying out undercover activities during <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s electoral process.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> also pledged to grant unconditional amnesty to all people arrested for inciting political disorder. <PERSON> Bernard </PERSON> <PERSON> Aronson </PERSON>, assistant secretary of state for inter-American affairs, visited <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION> and other Central American nations this week to urge against disbanding the Contras until after elections. <PERSON> Adolfo </PERSON> <PERSON> Calero </PERSON>, a member of the rebel political directorate, said he was `` elated that President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has come out unequivocally in favor of having the resistance remain as a viable force.'' The process of democratization in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>, promised by the leftist <ORGANIZATION> Sandinista </ORGANIZATION> government, remains to be seen, <PERSON> Calero </PERSON> said. `` You do not take down the scaffold before the building is finished,'' he said. A senior <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> official in <LOCATION> Washsington </LOCATION>, briefing reporters on the <PERSON> Aronson </PERSON> trip, cited complaints that the Sandinista government is mounting raids against suspected Contra sympathizers in northern <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> and has failed to create fair conditions for political opponents. All <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military aid to the Contras was cut off a year ago and the rebels now receive a trickle of non-lethal assistance, such as food and boots.
</TEXT>
