<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Japan-Ozone     08-04 0177</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Japan-Ozone,0182</SECOND>
<HEAD>Toyota to End Use of CFCs by 1995</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s largest automobile manufacturer said Friday it will stop using chlorofluorocarbons, which are blamed for hurting the Earth's protective ozone layer. By 1995, <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> will discontinue use of the gas, which it uses for cleaning, cooling and foaming during manufacturing, said spokesman <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> McMillan </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION> used 2,800 tons of CFCs during 1988, he said. The Toyota group, which includes affiliated parts suppliers, used 9,500 tons in that year, <PERSON> McMillan </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION>'s action follows a move by <ORGANIZATION> Nissan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s second - and third-largest automakers, to cease using the gas by the mid-1990s The auto industry consumes 14 percent of all CFCs used in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, makers say. In 1987, 38 countries agreed in <LOCATION> Montreal </LOCATION> to reduce production and use of the gases. Under the Montreal Protocol, participating countries must have frozen their consumption of CFCs at the 1986 level by July 1, 1898, and reduce consumption to 5 percent of the 1986 level by the end of 1999.
