<HEAD>China Says Intellectuals Will Be Spared, But Punishes Fang</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to DELETE reference to throat cancer.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELAINE KURTENBACH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> said Friday it would not crack down on intellectuals even though some participated in recent pro-democracy protests, but it also stripped leading dissident <PERSON> Fang </PERSON> <PERSON> Lizhi </PERSON> of his post on an academic board. The <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>, meanwhile, refused immediate comment on reports by a Japanese news agency that senior leader <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> <PERSON> Xiaoping </PERSON> is gravely ill with prostate cancer. An unsigned commentary in the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> newspaper <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> appeared aimed at reassuring <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s educated elite, some of whom have come under sharp attack for supporting what the party calls `` bourgeois liberalism'' _ Western liberal ideas _ and the student-led pro-democracy movement `` There has been some concern as to whether the party's policy toward intellectuals would change. It is necessary to reaffirm that -LRB- it -RRB- has not changed and will not change,'' the commentary said. It called the intellectuals who took part in the student movement `` scum of the intellectuals -LRB- who -RRB- do not represent the intellectuals'' and `` enemies of the party and of the people.'' `` It is in the interest of the workers, peasants and intellectuals to punish them, and the party will protect that interest,'' it said. `` Those who were under the influence of the wave of bourgeois liberalism ... will elevate their understanding and continue to make contributions'' to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s modernization program, it said. The army's violent crackdown on mass demonstrations in early June has ushered in a new era of repression. Chinese are urged to turn in friends and family members who participated in the protests, and many must attend weekly political study sessions reminiscent of the ultra-leftist Cultural Revolution. The crackdown has brought an end to a period of relatively free political debate. Newspapers once more are under strict party control, and the works of 10 writers, including <PERSON> Fang </PERSON>, have been banned. The official <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> said Friday that <PERSON> Fang </PERSON>, an astrophysicist, was relieved of his position on the <ORGANIZATION> Academic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Degrees </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> under the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s Cabinet, and of his qualification to tutor doctoral students. <PERSON> Fang </PERSON>, who took refuge inside the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> with his wife shortly after the crackdown, already had lost another minor post but apparently still retains his main job at the <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Observatory </LOCATION>. The government has issued arrest warrants for <PERSON> Fang </PERSON> and his wife, physics professor <PERSON> Li </PERSON> <PERSON> Shuxian </PERSON>, for allegedly inciting pro-democracy protests and has demanded that the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> turn them over to Chinese authorities. Thousands of students, intellectuals and others are believed to have been arrested for participating in the seven-week movement. During the 1966-76 Cultural Revolution, intellectuals were severely persecuted as `` class enemies.'' Since then, <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> hasd emphasized the need for skilled and talented intellectuals to help <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> modernize. The educated elite, however, remains among the lowest paid and most politically vulnerable of all Chinese. In <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> on Friday, the <ORGANIZATION> Jiji </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> quoted unidentified Chinese sources as saying the health of <PERSON> Deng </PERSON>, 84, had deteriorated seriously a few days ago, and that emergency medical personnel were sent to care for him at a coastal resort east of <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>. It quoted doctors as saying they were discussing whether <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> was too ill to be moved to <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>, where better facilities were available. An employee in the information department of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> said he had received many queries about <PERSON> Deng </PERSON>'s health but could issue no immediate response. There was no answer Friday night at the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>'s news office. In another development, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s Home Ofice said it has granted political asylum to three Chinese diplomats and is considering an application from a fourth. A Home Office spokesman identified one of the diplomats given asylum <LOCATION> Nin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hongshan </LOCATION>, a second secretary in the embassy's educational section He said the others were all middle-ranking diplomats but would not identify them. In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, two Chinese exiles said a group that aims to provide a democratic alternative to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> will hold its inaugural congress of 120 delegates from around the world next month. The congress will be held secretly in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> and will involve exiled student leaders and intellectuals as well as individuals traveling surreptitiously from <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, said the exiles, <PERSON> Wan </PERSON> <PERSON> Runnan </PERSON>