<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A former high-ranking aide to Mayor <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Koch </PERSON> has been indicted for perjury in testimony regarding political patronage, officials announced today, less than six weeks before the mayoral primary election. <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> DeVincenzo </PERSON>, former special assistant to <PERSON> Koch </PERSON>, was accused of lying to the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> on Government Integrity on July 13 and 21 last year and in a public hearing of that commission this past Jan. 11. <PERSON> DeVincenzo </PERSON>, 46, told the commission that politically connected job applicants were not given favorable treatment, a position contradicted by other witnesses. <PERSON> DeVincenzo </PERSON> appeared in state court today, pleaded innocent and was released on his own recognizance pending an Aug. 11 hearing. Assistant District Attorney <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Cherkasky </PERSON>, who announced today that the 11-count indictment issued up Thursday, noted that patronage is not illegal. Perjury, however, is punishable by a maximum of seven years in prison. <PERSON> DeVincenzo </PERSON> was responsible for the city's <ORGANIZATION> Talent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>, which ostensibly recruited minorities to fill city posts. Critics claim the program actually was a patronage mill, doling out the highest paying jobs to whites. Files relating to the program's operations were destroyed at the beginning of city corruption scandals. <PERSON> DeVincenzo </PERSON> and others told the commission that the destruction of those records was routine and not part of a cover-up. The <ORGANIZATION> Talent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>, which operated out of an office in the basement of City Hall, has become a campaign issue as <PERSON> Koch </PERSON> seeks the Democratic nomination to run for a fourth term in November. District Attorney <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Morgenthau </PERSON>, in an telephone interview, defended the timing of the indictment. `` We did consider it,'' <PERSON> Morgenthau </PERSON> said. `` But we could not be in the role of censor, deciding what the public could and could not hear.'' He said that if possible, the charges would have been filed earlier, but `` we moved as expeditiously as we could.'' The commission was told that some of the files at the <ORGANIZATION> Talent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> were marked with color codes, indicating a party leader or other political sponsor who might have referred an applicant to <PERSON> DeVincenzo </PERSON>. His own assistant, <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hein </PERSON>, testified that <PERSON> DeVincenzo </PERSON> had ordered him in February 1986 to `` cleanse'' the employment computer and paper files of `` any references to political figures.'' In February, <PERSON> Koch </PERSON> announced that he had asked for <PERSON> DeVincenzo </PERSON>'s resignation But <PERSON> DeVinenzo </PERSON> had already filed papers to resign, ensuring his pension of $ 52,000 a year.
