<HEAD>`I'll Call You Back If I Can Find My Phone Under This Stuff'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE FEINSILBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> consulting firm has thrown down the gauntlet. Atop last week's milk carton, the call of the roll from the 1964 Republican National Convention and a copy of the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> Star, which folded Aug. 7, 1981, turns up an announcement looking for the messiest desk in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. The prize, worth $ 415, is free tuition in the firm's training course in time management. That is, how to have a tidy desk and, presumably, tidy habits. The offer comes from Priority Management, which trains people in how to arrange their day, manage their time, keep their files and, above all else, prioritize. Priority Management has no intention of inspecting the nominated desks to separate the truly disgusting from the merely slovenly. It will settle for photographic evidence, says <PERSON> Cynthia </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rozzo </PERSON>, director of marketing and the brains behind the contest. True to form, this is what she has to say, unprompted: `` A cluttered desk is a cluttered mind.'' The contest entries, says Ms. <PERSON> Rozzo </PERSON>, on whose desk there is a place for everything and everything is in its place, will be scrutinized for these symptoms: _ Multiple calendars -LRB- They lead to overbooking, says Ms. <PERSON> Rozzo </PERSON>. -RRB- _ Those little pink phone messages, scattered around -LRB- One may return yesterday's call more than once. -RRB- _ Reminders on scraps of paper, strewn about -LRB- Tch, tch. -RRB- _ Someday files -LRB- as in `` someday I'll get around to it'' -RRB- _ Leaning towers in the `` in'' box _ Open files atop the desk `` Open files distract from the task at hand,'' Ms. <PERSON> Rozzo </PERSON> said, yielding to an impulse to instruct. `` Let's say you have four projects going on at the same time. People usually have files from all four on their desks. We show people they should n't do that. We say put three of the files on some other piece of office furniture. We love credenzas. People who make credenzas love us.'' Ms. <PERSON> Rozzo </PERSON> said her firm teaches people how to organize their day, how to say `` No, I ca n't talk to you,'' how to delegate and how to keep a boss or colleague from laying on an unscheduled chore by asking, `` Is it urgent and important? Can it wait?'' Instead of saying, `` I'll get back to you,'' says Ms. <PERSON> Rozzo </PERSON>, `` you should say, ` I will call you on Aug. 9.''' One should not say, `` I will call you on Aug. 9 if I can find my telephone under this pile of stuff.'' That is very untidy. It will not do.
