an infant, airline officials said. Officials said pilot <PERSON> Petros </PERSON> <PERSON> Moutzoureas </PERSON> was an hour into his domestic flight from <LOCATION> Salonica </LOCATION> in northern <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION> when he radioed his final position as he made his approach for landing. The plane disappeared from <LOCATION> Athens </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Salonica </LOCATION> radar screens when it was about 25 miles off the island's northwest coast. When it failed to land at 5:30 p.m., officials ordered and air and sea search. Transport and Communications Minister <PERSON> Nikos </PERSON> <PERSON> Gelestathis </PERSON> said all the victims were Greeks, although <PERSON> Yannis </PERSON> <PERSON> Orphanides </PERSON>, a Canadian of <LOCATION> Greek </LOCATION> descent, said in <LOCATION> Salonica </LOCATION> that his parents, brother, wife and infant son _ all Canadians from <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION> _ were killed. The Canadian Embassy in <LOCATION> Athens </LOCATION> said three other passengers who had booked their tickets in <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION> also could have been Canadian citizens. An embassy official said they were checking with their foreign office in <LOCATION> Ottawa </LOCATION> to confirm their nationality.
