<HEAD>Ambassador Says U.S. Bases Vital to Development</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 American military bases in the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> play a vital role in regional stability and should be maintained despite favorable changes in the Soviet political climate, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ambassador said Friday. Ambassador <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Platt </PERSON> told a seminar at the University of the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> that economic development in the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> and elsewhere in <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> `` can not happen without security.'' `` There is a regional consensus that the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> security umbrella is as important now, even in this changing era, as it was before,'' <PERSON> Platt </PERSON> said. `` If we are to have a successful new partnership, we will need continuing <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> involvement in the security of this region,'' <PERSON> Platt </PERSON> said. `` Our military facilities here in the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> are one element of the security equation.'' The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> are expected to begin preliminary talks this year on whether to extend the lease on the six American installations, which expires in 1991. After 1991, any extension must be approved by two-thirds of the 23-member Philippine <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. Opposition to the bases has been growing here. Several leading politicians have called for the bases to be closed in 1991 or phased out over a 10-year period. President <PERSON> Corazon </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> has refused to say whether she will support an extension. <PERSON> Platt </PERSON> said the economy of the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> depends on trade and the bases play a vital role in protecting sea lanes. `` There is a balance between the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Platt </PERSON> said. `` And the maintenance of that balance creates the stability that everybody is trying to preserve. The maintenance of that stability provides the background for the progress, the economic progress, that everybody wants.'' <PERSON> Platt </PERSON> noted that the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> is undergoing political changes that `` are welcome to us. `` But we do n't think it is smart, and we do n't think it makes sense, to dismantle the alliance relationships that we have while we are assessing what these changes are.'' In a related development, Filipino diplomats said a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> congressional delegation will visit the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> to look into the possibility of withdrawing some troops in the next few years. About 40,000 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops, civilian employees and military dependents are stationed in the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>. The diplomats said Reps. <PERSON> Patricia </PERSON> <PERSON> Schroeder </PERSON>, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Murtha </PERSON>, and <PERSON> Dante </PERSON> <PERSON> Fascell </PERSON> will arrive Aug. 11.
