House</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two education leaders said Friday it will take money as well as leadership to turn President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> into the education president he has said he wants to be. `` As long as there is a budget deadlock and the administration has its hands tied by its own budget policies, it's going to be very difficult for <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to be the education president,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Atwell </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION>, an umbrella group for all <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> colleges and universities. <PERSON> Atwell </PERSON> and <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Rosser </PERSON>, president of the 830-member <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Independent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Colleges </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Universities </ORGANIZATION>, said they hope <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s education summit next month with the nation's governors will include higher education as well as the elementary and secondary grades. `` There are very serious problems'' in higher education, <PERSON> Rosser </PERSON> said, among them `` an incredible need for science facilities'' and more federal money for research support and student aid. `` It can not be simply leadership at the national level. It's got to be money,'' he said. <PERSON> Atwell </PERSON> and <PERSON> Rosser </PERSON> said higher education did not fare as well as the lower grades in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> appropriations bill for fiscal 1990 that passed earlier this week. `` The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> appropriations overall are really quite insufficient and could do great damage to students,'' <PERSON> Atwell </PERSON> said. `` We're going to be working very hard to do better in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> in higher education than we did in the House.'' <PERSON> Atwell </PERSON> and <PERSON> Rosser </PERSON> also pledged to continue fighting for a separate aid program for students at for-profit schools, which have a loan default rate four times as high as the 9 percent average for four-year institutions. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> committee said it was concerned about sky-high default rates at some trade schools and said there would be `` a full review'' of defaults and other problems in the financial aid program next year when the Higher Education Act comes up for reapproval. The for-profit schools are attracting an ever-greater proportion of grants and loans, some of them for classes of dubious value or students with dubious ability, educators say. The shift prompted <PERSON> Atwell </PERSON>'s controversial call for a separate aid program and has also resulted in colleges and universities devoting more of their own resources to campus-based student aid. <PERSON> Rosser </PERSON> said school-sponsored aid rose from $ 900 million in 1979 to $ 3.5 billion in the past year at the private, non-profit schools he represents. <PERSON> Rosser </PERSON> said faculty salaries still do n't match the purchasing power they had in 1972 while `` staff salaries are much lower and probably in much worse shape.'' In addition, he said, schools are spending money on science equipment that ca n't wait and a whole array of new services designed to meet student needs and help schools stay competitive _ career placement departments, security forces, drug and alcohol abuse programs, and counselors to help minority students and others with special needs.
