<HEAD>US Resumes Haiti Aid Program</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has agreed to provide <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION> with $ 10 million in food aid, the first such assistance since the failed elections of November 1987, it was announced Friday. Under terms of an agreement signed Thursday in <LOCATION> Port-au-Prince </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION> will receive about 45,000 metric tons of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> wheat, which it will sell on the local market. Proceeds will be used for development projects. In making the announcement, which was first reported Thursday on Haitian television, the <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> said <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> approved the new aid in recognition of continuing progress by the interim government of Gen. Prosper Avril toward free elections. The decision also was based on <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION>'s cooperation with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in narcotics interdiction efforts, AID said. The Haitian government canceled the November 1987 national elections after an outburst of violence on the morning of the balloting claimed at least 50 dead and dozens wounded. The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration suspended $ 62 million in economic aid hours after <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION> disbanded the national electoral council. The only assistance provided since then has been for an anti-narcotics program and for emergency aid following Hurricane Gilbert last year. Humanitarian aid to the <LOCATION> Haitian </LOCATION> people through non-governmental organizations has continued.
