 </ORGANIZATION> quoted a security source as saying that from Tuesday to Thursday, the air force flew 380 missions over areas where they suspected there were enemy batteries. Supported by artillery and rockets, the air force carried out attacks on the <LOCATION> Paghman </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>, 15 miles west of <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>, and in a 15-mile area east and southeast of the capital, <ORGANIZATION> Bakhtar </ORGANIZATION> reported Thursday. It quoted the security source as saying the government plans to expand the security belt around <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> to prevent rocket attacks. Most rockets used against <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> have a range of less than 20 miles, though longer range rockets also have been launched. No group has claimed responsibility for the recent attacks against <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>, though U.S.-backed guerrillas fighting to oust President <PERSON> Najib </PERSON>'s Soviet-backed government have said they were responsible for previous rocketing. The guerrillas say they aim at military targets and blame the government for attacks on schools, markets, bus stops and other civilian targets _ an allegation vehemently denied by the government.
