<HEAD>Appeal Filed In Age Discrimination Case Involving Vermont Jurist</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER GRAFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTPELIER, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Lawyers for the state of <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION> said Friday that they are appealing a federal judge's ruling that a 70-year-old state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> justice can not be forced to retire because of his age. Lawyers for the state of <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION> on Friday filed a notice in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Rutland </LOCATION> that the case was being appealed to the 2nd <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION>, based in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. At issue is whether a federal law prohibiting age discrimination applies to appointed state judges. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Gagliardi </PERSON> ruled last month that it does and struck down a state order that Justice <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> Peck </PERSON> retire. His ruling, in effect, nullified a section of the Vermont Constitution that requires all judges to retire at age 70. <PERSON> Peck </PERSON> turned 70 last December, but refused to retire and filed suit when the state ordered that he do so. Lawyer <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Gray </PERSON>, representing the state, said he filed a notice in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Rutland </LOCATION> that the state was appealing to the 2nd <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` The decision by the district court is inconsistent with other rulings on the question and we feel it appropriate that the issue be addressed by the 2nd Circuit,'' he said. Even though <PERSON> Peck </PERSON> won in the first round, he said he welcomed the appeal. `` I think it is fair to say that both sides want this to go as high as it can,'' said the justice, one of five on <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION>'s only appeals court `` The higher it goes, the greater an impact it will have,'' <PERSON> Peck </PERSON> said. `` What we really hope is that the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> will agree to hear this so that we can finally settle the question once and for all.'' <PERSON> Gagliardi </PERSON>'s ruling within the territory covered by the 2nd Circuit conflicts with rulings by a federal judge in <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> and the 1st <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION>, which said the federal law prohibiting discrimination does not apply to appointed state judges. `` We believe that the confusion coming out of these cases may make it more attractive for the -LRB- <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Supreme -RRB- court to agree to hear this,'' said <PERSON> Peck </PERSON>. The disagreement is whether the federal Age Discrimination in Employment Act supersedes state mandatory retirement provisions for judges. The law prohibits age discrimination, but excludes certain groups from the provision. The <ORGANIZATION> Equal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Employment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Opportunity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, which represents <PERSON> Peck </PERSON>, argues that judges do n't fall under any of the exceptions. <PERSON> Gray </PERSON> argues that judges fall under the exception granted for policymakers, and that the Constitution requires <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to state its intention clearly when it wants to regulate qualifications for such important state offices as judges. `` I expect our brief will address both the interpretation of the statute and the constitutional implications,'' <PERSON> Gray </PERSON> said. If the ruling stands under appeal, <PERSON> Peck </PERSON> can remain on the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> until his term expires in three years. He could also seek another six-year term.
