<HEAD>And, Lo, Ryukyu's Stone _ Replaced at Last _ Honors ``Great Mandarin''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In 1854, <PERSON> Commodore </PERSON> <PERSON> Matthew </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Perry </PERSON> docked his ships at <LOCATION> Okinawa </LOCATION> and, in telling of the wonders of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, mentioned the monument being built in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> in memory of `` the great mandarin,'' <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Washington </PERSON>. And, lo, the people of the Kingdom of <LOCATION> Ryukyu </LOCATION> _ <LOCATION> Okinawa </LOCATION> _ contributed a large stone from a quarry along with a 15th century temple bell. The stone was to be placed into the wall of the monument along with other commemorative stones and <PERSON> Perry </PERSON> planned to hang the bell at the top of the monument. The bell made it to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>; the stone did n't. But nobody noticed because by then the money to build the monument had run out and it resembled a tree stump for another 25 years. Besides, a civil war and other matters occupied <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. Fast forward 130 years to 1984. The <ORGANIZATION> Ryukyu </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Historical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION>, an <LOCATION> Okinawa </LOCATION> civic organization, comes to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> to see the famous <PERSON> Ryukyu </PERSON> stone and discovers it is n't there Now it is the first Friday in August 1989. The temperature is 94 degrees, almost too hot even for tourists. At a ceremony on the south side of the monument a replacement stone is unveiled by two of 10 students who came from <LOCATION> Okinawa </LOCATION> for the occasion. `` This is a very important day for <LOCATION> Okinawa </LOCATION>,'' says <PERSON> Yukiko </PERSON> <PERSON> Koja </PERSON>, one of the student delegates. `` This stone is important because it symbolizes our long friendship with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>.'' The Japanese ambassador, the honorable <PERSON> Nobuo </PERSON> <PERSON> Matsunaga </PERSON>, calls the occasion `` joyful'' and speaks of it as a cornerstone of future development of cooperation. Eight dancers in kimonos do the traditional opening dance of <LOCATION> Okinawa </LOCATION> as a record plays music. The lyrics are translated to `` today's happiness can be compared with the blossoming of a flower when touched by dew.'' Retired <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> Capt. <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Pineau </PERSON>, who organized <PERSON> Perry </PERSON>'s papers in the 1960s, tells the gathering that the last mention of the original stone was when it was transferred in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> When <PERSON> Perry </PERSON> received the stone from the <LOCATION> Okinawan </LOCATION> people, he said, there also was a bill for $ 80. Embarrassed Okinawan officials, <PERSON> Pineau </PERSON> said, apparently said they would take care of it. The new stone measures two feet by four feet by three inches and weighs 396 pounds. Part of it was hollowed out for 53 pebbles from nine <LOCATION> Okinawa </LOCATION> cities and 44 villages. It will be the 193rd commemorative stone in the monument, only 15 of them from foreign countries. It will be placed at the 310-foot level where the only people who will see it are those who make arrangements to go down the stairs of the 555-foot monument. As for the <ORGANIZATION> Gokokuji </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> _ it was never put in the monument. Instead it was on display at the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Naval Academy in <LOCATION> Annapolis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Md. </LOCATION>, until 1986 when it was returned to the people of <LOCATION> Okinawa </LOCATION> as a gesture of good will.
