<SECOND>AM-Poland,0375</SECOND>
<HEAD>Newspaper Reports Drop in Party Membership</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Communist Party membership dropped by 35,000 in the first half of 1989 and the party has lost more than 1 million members in the last decade, a leading party weekly reported. The article in the Saturday edition of <LOCATION> Polityka </LOCATION> also pointed out that nearly one-fifth of party members are retirees and that workers are a minority in the party, whose formal name is the Polish <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. Party membership stands just below 2.1 million, compared to 3.15 million in 1980, the article said, and most members occupy management posts. The article noted that the communist coalition received only about 25 percent of the vote for the freely elected <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> in June. `` So it is a minority, though a significant minority.'' This year, 42,000 members left the party, while only 7,000 joined. Among those who left, 11,500 quit, 8,800 were dropped from party rolls for showing `` lack of interest in party life,'' 8,000 changed jobs and did not re-register with the party at their new workplaces and 1,300 emigrated. The article did not specify what accounted for the remaining drop. The article quoted party documents as estimating only one-fourth of the party membership is active, 60 percent do not meet the party's rules for minimum participation and the remainder is generally `` passive.'' About one-third of the party membership thinks other political groups do more to aid society's interests than the party does, and about the same number do not believe it will be able to work out a program that will keep it in power past 1993, the article said. Under this year's accords, fully democratic elections are to be held that year. The article said retirees now account for a record 17.6 percent of the membership and the average age of a party member is 46 compared to 40 in 1980. Although it claims to be the party of the working class, only 37.5 percent of the party are workers, compared with 52.1 percent who are in the intelligentsia _ which refers to professions requiring higher education such as managers, teachers, professors, journalists, doctors and lawyers. The rest are in agriculture.
</TEXT>
