RSON> Mirecki </PERSON> was undergoing rescue-swimmer training when he panicked during a strenuous rescue drill, climbed from the pool and shouted that he was quitting Court-martial testimony indicated he had an unusual fear of being pushed under water and suffered heart failure and drowned after instructors pushed him back in the pool and held his head under water. The death of <PERSON> Fedie </PERSON> drew unusual attention because of the previous <PERSON> Mirecki </PERSON> investigation, which was pressed by <PERSON> Mirecki </PERSON>'s congressman after complaints were raised by his family about the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>'s handling of the case <PERSON> Fedie </PERSON> died during a different type of drill, one in which aviation trainees jump off a 12-foot tower and swim about 15 yards under water while wearing their flight suits. Most sailors go through similar drills during basic training. <PERSON> Fedie </PERSON> completed the exercise and was walking from the pool when he collapsed back into shallow water, witnesses said. Medical examiners said there was little doubt of a seizure, but they were uncertain whether it was triggered by the central nervous or cardiovascular systems, <PERSON> Hessler </PERSON> said.
