olitics will continue to prevail.'' <PERSON> Uno </PERSON> asked party members on Friday to refrain from factionalism in the presidential race. Half a dozen major factions in the party are separated more by personal and financial allegiances than their conservative political leanings. The large faction led by former Finance Minister <PERSON> Kiichi </PERSON> <PERSON> Miyazawa </PERSON> decided on Friday to support <PERSON> Hayashi </PERSON>, who belongs to one of the party's smallest groups. <PERSON> Seiichi </PERSON> <PERSON> Ohta </PERSON>, a leading member of the <PERSON> Miyazawa </PERSON> faction, branded <PERSON> Kaifu </PERSON>'s candidacy a product of back room deals involving large factions. `` It will disappoint the public,'' he said. Analysts said <PERSON> Kaifu </PERSON> remains the front-runner because of strong backing from factions led by former Prime Minister <PERSON> Noboru </PERSON> <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> and former Foreign Minister <PERSON> Shintaro </PERSON> <PERSON> Abe </PERSON>. The party's popular No. 2 official, <PERSON> Ryutaro </PERSON> <PERSON> Hashimoto </PERSON>, 52, formally declined to run Friday, saying his candidacy would further split the party. Former <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> head <PERSON> Ganri </PERSON> <PERSON> Yamashita </PERSON>, 68, had said he would run, but had to drop out Friday when he failed to draw enough support from party members to become a candidate. He said he and his supporters would back <PERSON> Hayashi </PERSON>.
