<HEAD>Alderman Tries Life on the Streets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A city alderman who left behind his wallet and his <ORGANIZATION> Cadillac </ORGANIZATION> to spend five days on the streets said he's gained a new perspective on what it's like to be homeless `` It was a good experience for me,'' <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Wooden </PERSON>, 39, said on his return Thursday to his job as senior spokesman for <ORGANIZATION> Humana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, the giant hospital company. `` I learned a lot.'' Wooden began his adventure Saturday, when he set off with a quarter in his pocket and a change of socks and underwear in a gym bag. Calling himself <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Wayne </PERSON>, he told people he was passing through town, out of work and looking for a job and a place to sleep. After a night on a bench at a downtown plaza, Wooden found his way to a shelter _ and began to enjoy himself, he said. He was `` adopted'' by a man named <PERSON> Frank </PERSON>, who, along with <PERSON> Wooden </PERSON>, was staying at the Wayside Christian Mission downtown. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> showed Wooden how to panhandle. The alderman said he did n't feel very comfortable asking people for spare change; most ignored him or mumbled that they did n't have change. <PERSON> Wooden </PERSON> said that by Wednesday he fit in with the men at the shelter. That afternoon, a group of them sat on a corner, laughing. The other men were drinking, and Wooden smoked cigars he bought after selling his blood for $ 15. `` We had the best time,'' he said. `` I like to meet people. So I found that part of this adventure fun and exciting. `` They've all got serious problems,'' <PERSON> Wooden </PERSON> said. `` But they're making the best of a bad situation, and some of them are managing to have fun and laugh and joke. Wooden had planned to stay on the streets a week, but said that by Wednesday he'd done what he set out to do: `` meeting some of the people, knowing what kind of services were available and really living the life.'' The alderman said he might not have time to introduce ordinances or otherwise help the homeless during the six months left in his term, but plans to ask workers in missions and shelters what the Board of Aldermen can do for <LOCATION> Louisville </LOCATION>'s estimated 1,200 homeless. He said he might volunteer his own time. <PERSON> Wooden </PERSON> said that as he drove to work Thursday, he spotted some of the men he'd gotten to know at the shelter. `` For the first time, I can see them as real human beings with feelings and families,'' he said.
