<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Shrimpers could abandon turtle excluder devices in favor of limited trawls to keep endangered sea turtles from drowning in their nets under proposed temporary <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> regulations completed Friday and scheduled to take effect Tuesday. Department spokesman <PERSON> Reed </PERSON> <PERSON> Boatright </PERSON> said Secretary <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mosbacher </PERSON> finished the proposal Friday and would submit the plan limiting trawl times to 105 minutes to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Court Judge <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Hogan </PERSON> on Monday. In a court hearing Thursday, <PERSON> Hogan </PERSON> gave <PERSON> Mosbacher </PERSON> until Monday to draft a plan to protect endangered sea turtles from becoming entangled in shrimpers' nets. Environmentalists, however, said Friday that the <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON>'s ridley sea turtle faces quick extinction if the government abandons turtle excluder devices in favor of limited shrimp-fishing trawl times. The Center for Marine Conservation and other organizations want <PERSON> Mosbacher </PERSON> to require shrimpers to use turtle excluder devices. Shrimpers, however, say the devices reduce their catch and threaten their livelihood. The center's <PERSON> Marydele </PERSON> <PERSON> Donnelly </PERSON> said limited trawl times `` condemn the <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON>'s ridley sea turtle to extinction within this century.'' `` A major confrontation looms ahead on sea turtle protection,'' Ms. <PERSON> Donnelly </PERSON> said. `` Secretary <PERSON> Mosbacher </PERSON> needs to move swiftly to enforce federal environmental laws protecting endangered species. Restricted tow times, unlike TEDs, will hasten the day when sea turtles will no longer exist in American waters.'' <PERSON> Uhder </PERSON> <PERSON> Mosbacher </PERSON>'s proposal, shrimpers would have about 7 -LCB- minutes to get their nets in, and 7 -LCB- minutes to get them out, with actual trawl time limited to 90 minutes, <PERSON> Boatright </PERSON> said. While the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> contends that sea turtles can survive submerged for 90 minutes, conservationists argue limited trawl times are ineffective in reducing turtle mortality and can not be enforced. The center said the government's most recent analysis found that one in four sea turtles will drown during a tow time of 105 minutes. It said gulf shrimpers normally leave their nets in the water for two to 10 hours. <PERSON> Mosbacher </PERSON> suspended enforcement of the turtle excluder device regulations July 24 after shrimpers protested the law.
