<HEAD>At British Auction, American Civil War Newspapers Hottest Sellers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 American newspapers that recorded events from the Civil War were the hottest sellers Friday at an auction of old newspapers, the auctioneers <PERSON> Bonhams </PERSON> said. The newspapers were sold by an anonymous English collector who said his family was `` being driven bananas by all my newspapers all over the house,'' but that he was so avid he was keeping newspapers mentioning the auction. About 300 newspapers were sold for a total of about $ 5,000, said auctioneer <PERSON> Duncan </PERSON> <PERSON> Chilcott </PERSON>. `` The trend from the sale would suggest that there's a great market for 17th century and 18th century newspapers and an even better market for <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> newspapers,'' <PERSON> Chilcott </PERSON> said. `` American newspapers describing the Civil War, they were most eagerly sought after, they were the ones we had the most competition for from the bidders,'' he said. The oldest newspaper in the sale, The Perfect Diurnall, of Aug. 28, 1648, fetched the highest price, about $ 246. The newspaper, which reported <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> Cromwell </PERSON>'s new model army capturing the town of <LOCATION> Colchester </LOCATION>, was produced by <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> and was principally a record of parliamentary debates. The older newspapers were generally in better condition because the quality of modern paper is such that a newspaper exposed to light can turn yellow within a week. The most modern newspapers for sale _ recording the Falklands War and the wedding of Prince <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> and <PERSON> Diana </PERSON> _ did n't sell, <PERSON> Chilcott </PERSON> said.
