ence-peddling inquiries. <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> claimed thta some of the nominations were being held hostage to legislation sought by individual members, while `` in some cases they -LRB- senators -RRB- want commitments on their own candidates for other jobs.'' `` Some cases, it appeared to be just political,'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> added. The White House and the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> are also feuding over whether <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> staff aides should be allowed to study confidential <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> reports on <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s nominees. The White House now only permits senators to review this material. `` We feel very strongly that the privacy of individual nominees is such that members of the staff should not be able to rummage trough people's private backgrounds and resumes and <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> files and we register a very strong protest against that idea,'' the spokesman said. `` He feels very strongly that senators are elected to make these kinds of judgments,'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said.
