<HEAD>Christian Science Couple Found Innocent on Involuntary Manslaughter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA ROSA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A Christian Science couple were acquitted Friday of involuntary manslaughter but convicted of child endangerment for relying on prayer instead of medical treatment for their dying infant daughter. <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Rippberger </PERSON>, 35, and <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Middleton </PERSON>, 39, members of the <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Christ </ORGANIZATION>, Scientist, face up to four years state in prison for the 1984 meningitis death of their 8-month-old daughter <PERSON> Natalie </PERSON> <PERSON> Susan </PERSON>. Sentencing is set for Oct. 12. <PERSON> Rippberger </PERSON> and <PERSON> Middleton </PERSON> belong to a church founded by visionary <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> Eddy </PERSON>, who believed disease is a physical manifestation of `` errors of the mind.'' `` The jury showed remarkable intelligence in handing down this verdict,'' said prosecutor <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Dunn </PERSON> outside court. The family's attorney, <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Mackenroth </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Sacramento </LOCATION>, said he will appeal During the seven-week trial before <ORGANIZATION> Sonoma </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> Judge <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> von </PERSON> <PERSON> der </PERSON> <PERSON> Mehden </PERSON>, the president of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pediatrics </ORGANIZATION> testified that there is a 95 percent survival rate when the infection is treated by a drug called defuroxime. The 12-member jury began deliberating the case Wednesday. <PERSON> Rippberger </PERSON> and <PERSON> Middleton </PERSON> were charged with two felonies, involuntary manslaughter and child endangerment. <PERSON> Mackenroth </PERSON> contended the couple were guilty only of following their religious beliefs in seeking a cure through spiritual healing. <PERSON> Dunn </PERSON> said the couple may have acted correctly according to the tenets of their religion, but their actions must be evaluated against the standards of conduct established by law, that of an `` ordinarily prudent, careful person.''
