<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> could make the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>'s job easier by writing laws clearly, eliminating the need for time-consuming court interpretations, Justice <PERSON> Byron </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON> said in a speech Friday. In the speech prepared for delivery at the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>'s convention, <PERSON> White </PERSON> said fellow Justice <PERSON> Antonin </PERSON> <PERSON> Scalia </PERSON> has revived the debate over statutory language vs. legislative history. In the past 50 years, courts trying to determine congressional intent have looked at the legislative history of laws as well as the wording of the statutes, <PERSON> White </PERSON> said. Such history includes committee hearings and reports, floor debates and conference committee actions. <PERSON> White </PERSON> said a nearly 100-year-old high court decision _ Holy <ORGANIZATION> Trinity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> vs. <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> _ which allowed the interpretation of even a clear statute based on legislative history, `` barely'' survived the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>'s last session. In their interpretations, the courts begin with the statutory language, which if thought clearly to relect legislative intent, is followed, he said. However, `` most statutory cases involve not plain, but ambiguous language, and in these cases resort to legislative history has been the usual course,'' <PERSON> White </PERSON> said. `` This is often a very large undertaking, taking hours and hours of effort by judges, law clerks, and librarians, to say nothing of the time lawyers spend and charge for seeking to present the materials that the judiciary has indicated are relevant to decision.'' With the ever-increasing complexity of subjects considered by courts, more people, including <PERSON> Scalia </PERSON>, advocate a return to interpreting statutes based almost wholly on the legislation's text, <PERSON> White </PERSON> said `` The statute as it is written, it is said, is what <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> enacted, not statements in hearings, not discussion of statutory terms contained in committee reports, and not statements on the floor,'' said <PERSON> White </PERSON>, who was appointed to the court by President <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> in 1962. White said <PERSON> Scalia </PERSON>, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> appointee, would confine the review of legislative history to cases where the statuatory language itself `` produces an absurdity.'' The debate over how statutes should be interpreted `` is extremely important since it involves how the courts may best carry out the will of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>,'' <PERSON> White </PERSON> said, adding that in some cases <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> may be vague on purpose, to force court decisions. White mentioned several other areas where <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, as the major source of changes in federal law, could `` simplify our work and at the same time make its intent known..'' _ When enacting laws, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> should include a statute of limitations, he said _ <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> sometimes creates what seems to be a right, but fails to provide a remedy, creating a recurring legal issue over whether the seeming beneficiary of the right has a private remedy in federal court, he said. _ Regarding conflicts between federal and state laws, <PERSON> White </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> should make its intentions clear when it plans to supersede state law. _ White said <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> should clarify `` obvious uncertainties'' over statutes mandating the payment of lawyers' fees by losing defendants. More than 8,000 lawyers are attending the convention, which continues through Wednesday. The dinner was sponsored by the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judicature </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION>.
