<HEAD>Senate Votes to Extend Debt Limit to $2.87 Trillion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> voted Friday night to temporarily extend the government's debt limit by $ 70 billion to $ 2.87 trillion, granting it authority to borrow enough money to function through the next three months. On a voice vote, the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> gave final approval to the extension and sent it to President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> for his signature. Had the lawmakers not approved the measure before leaving for their four-week summer recess, the government would have run out of money during their vacation and toppled into an unprecedented default. The bill, which the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> had approved on Tuesday, provides enough borrowing authority to see the government through Oct. 31. On Nov. 1, the temporary authority would lapse and the legal limit on the federal debt will lapse back to its current ceiling of $ 2.8 trillion. By that time, lawmakers hope to complete a long-range permanent debt limit extension to more than $ 3.1 trillion, enough borrowing for about a year. Many legislators hope the long-term extension will contain the elements of a budget deal between <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration for fiscal 1991, which begins Oct. 1, 1990. Legislative leaders spent much of the last several weeks trying to dissuade lawmakers from offering amendments to the debt limit measure. The extension, considered must-pass legislation, is a favorite target for members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> with bills that are too controversial to pass if standing alone. The government needs legal authority to borrow money because it runs a deficit every year, a shortfall that has hovered at around $ 150 billion annually for the last three years. It gets the rest of the money it needs each year by borrowing it. When the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration took office in 1981, the national debt was just above $ 900 billion.
