 A lesbian minister who said she was the victim of two anti-gay attacks last month changed her story when police confronted her with evidence some of her injuries were self-inflicted, authorities said Friday. <PERSON> Lynn </PERSON> <PERSON> Griffis </PERSON>, an assistant pastor at the <ORGANIZATION> Metropolitan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> San </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Francisco </ORGANIZATION>, resigned from her duties two hours after being placed on administrative leave Thursday night, said Rev. <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitulski </PERSON>. `` As a church, we have a lot of compassion for <PERSON> Lynn </PERSON>, and whatever the truth is, we want to know what the truth is,'' <PERSON> Mitulski </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Griffis </PERSON> has left town and he does n't expect to hear from her again, he said. <PERSON> Griffis </PERSON> said she was attacked first on July 12, hit on the head with a shovel after surprising an assailant who broke into her garage and scrawled anti-gay graffiti on the wall. She received eight stitches. She later alleged that she was abducted July 27 in the <LOCATION> Haight-Ashbury </LOCATION> area by two so-called `` skinheads'' who threw her into a car, beat her up and threatened to kill her before releasing her. Police Chief <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Jordan </PERSON> said her account of the first attack was consistent with the evidence, but the medical examiner said physical evidence failed to match her account of a second attack. <PERSON> Jordan </PERSON> declined to detail the inconsistencies, but a source close to the case told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> that Medical Examiner <PERSON> Boyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Stephens </PERSON> determined the injuries she allegedly suffered from the skinheads were self-inflicted. <PE