<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> LONDON </LOCATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- _ Two men convicted 25 years ago in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s `` Great Train Robbery'' case were back in prison Friday after pleading guilty to drug-trafficking charges. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Wisbey </PERSON>, 59, was sentenced to 10 years in prison and <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Hussey </PERSON>, 56, was given a 7-year sentence for drug dealing. Both men had been convicted of participating in the Great Train Robbery of Aug. 8, 1963, when a gang of 15 men stole $ 7 million from a mail train. `` You are both old enough and experienced enough to know exactly what you were doing and your motive was greed in each case, regardless of the welfare of your fellow citizens,'' Judge <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Sanders </PERSON> told the defendants at <ORGANIZATION> Snaresbrook </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Crown </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in east <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> before sentencing them Friday. <PERSON> Hussey </PERSON> and <PERSON> Wisbey </PERSON> were each sentenced to 30 years in jail in 1964 for their part in the train robbery. <PERSON> Hussey </PERSON> was released in December 1975 and Wisbey the following year. At a hearing in the drugs case police testified that they saw the two men exchanging bags containing cocaine in a park. Detective Sgt. <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Gill </PERSON> told the court police seized 5.3 pounds of drugs with a street value of more than $ 930,000. <PERSON> Sanders </PERSON> ordered confiscation of about $ 76,000 found by police at two addresses and with <PERSON> Wisbey </PERSON>'s wife <PERSON> Irene </PERSON>. <PERSON> Wisbey </PERSON>, who pleaded guilty, was sentenced to 10 years for supplying 2.2 pounds of cocaine to <LOCATION> Hussey </LOCATION>. He also was sentenced to 10 years for possession of cocaine with intent to supply and three months for possessing marijuana. The sentence