<HEAD>Half Disapprove of Kidnapping</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Half of Americans questioned in a poll disapprove of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s kidnapping of a Shiite Moslem cleric, according to results released Friday. A similar proportion thought President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> had been `` not tough enough'' in handling the hostage crisis, according to the <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News-Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> poll of 711 adults on Wednesday and Thursday. Still, almost as many approved <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s handling of the situation. The proportion considering <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> a `` reliable ally,'' or one that can be trusted to cooperate with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> `` in almost any circumstances,'' fell to the lowest level in the eight years that question had been asked, 29 percent. Forty-eight percent said <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> should return the kidnapped man and 35 percent said he should not be returned. The rest had no opinion. Thirty percent approved of the kidnapping in the first place and 51 percent disapproved. Fifty-one percent said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> had not been tough enough, 35 percent said his reaction had been `` just about right'' and 1 percent said he had been too tough. When asked to approve or disapprove the president's handling of the crisis, 47 percent approved and 35 percent disapproved. Forty-eight percent said <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> should return its captive and 35 percent said it should not. The proportion characterizing <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> as `` not reliable'' rose to 53 percent from 46 percent giving a similar response in April, while those judging <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> reliable fell from 51 percent to 29 percent. Since 1981, the proportion applying the term `` reliable'' to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> had fluctuated from 40 percent to 64 percent. Those returning a judgment of `` not reliable'' had ranged between 24 percent and 56 percent. In a sample of 711 people, the margin of error is 4.5 percentage points either way, the poll said.
