<FIRST>s i BC-NorthernIrelandToday Adv13-2Takes   08-04 0774</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Northern Ireland Today, Adv 13-2 Takes,0795</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv13</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Aug. 13 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Northern Ireland Today _ 20 Years After Strife Began</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note anniversary is Aug. 14</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto, LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> erupted into violence on Aug. 14, 1969. Twenty years and 2,740 deaths later, the violence continues. But much has changed in recent years and some in the <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> province are beginning to see the foundations of a solution. Here is a report by an <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> correspondent who covers <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> regularly.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By MARCUS ELIASON</NOTE>
<NOTE>Associated Press Writer</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 All Mrs. <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON>'s neighbors are gone. The house she and her husband bought on <PERSON> Roe </PERSON> <PERSON> St. </PERSON> stands alone in a no-man's land, its windows protected by steel mesh and a tall corrugated wall separating the Roman Catholic couple from <ORGANIZATION> Protestant </ORGANIZATION> families 200 yards down the street. <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON>'s neighborhood once was mixed, with Protestants and Roman Catholics living side by side. But <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>'s violence came to <PERSON> Roe </PERSON> <PERSON> St. </PERSON> and the stonings and firebombings proved more than Mrs. <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON>'s neighbors could bear They went off to live among their own and authorities tore down their houses. But the <ORGANIZATION> Murphys </ORGANIZATION> held out. It all happened not 20 years ago, when `` The Troubles'' were at their worst in the <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> province, also known as Ulster, but just five months ago, and the houses razed were not hovels but new showcases of a <LOCATION> Belfast </LOCATION> rising from the Victorian slums. `` It's something of an indictment of society here,'' says <PERSON> Ivan </PERSON> <PERSON> Maginnis </PERSON> of the Housing Executive that had to make the decision. `` It's an awful tragedy.'' It's easy to conclude from this million-dollar exercise that little has changed in <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> since British troops arrived Aug. 14, 1969 to separate rioting Protestants from their Catholic neighbors. The death toll is over 2,740 and rising almost week by week. The Catholic unemployment rate is 2 -LCB- times that of Protestants. A political solution still looks far off. And yet one finds a glimmer of optimism in <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> today. Violence has diminished from a peak of 467 killings in 1972 to an average of 80 a year in the 1980s. Recent elections suggest a weakening of the hard-liners on both sides of the divide and a boost for the moderates. In the <LOCATION> Irish </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION> to the south, the political mold shaped in the country's 1921-23 civil war has cracked and opened new possibilities for a solution that can accommodate both <ORGANIZATION> Unionist </ORGANIZATION> and Nationalist in <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>. The Unionists are the majority Protestants intent on retaining union with <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, and Nationalists are the 40-percent <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> minority whose aspirations lean to the <LOCATION> Irish </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION>. The Irish government in <LOCATION> Dublin </LOCATION> has not renounced its claim to <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>. It simply does n't state it too loudly. It is in consensus with the <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> government that nothing can change without <ORGANIZATION> Protestant </ORGANIZATION> consent. In a half dozen of <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>'s 26 district councils, moderate Catholics and Protestants have joined in coalitions to shut out the extremists on both sides. <PERSON> Dungannon </PERSON>, a town of 15,000 in the center of the province, was once a bastion of Unionist supremacy and discrimination. Now its mixed council has a committee to promote cross-community understanding and sends <ORGANIZATION> Protestant </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> children on vacations together. The whole island, north and south, is in intellectual ferment over the prospect that a united <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> _ beginning with the lowering of trade barriers in the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> in 1992 _ will subsume old nationalist rivalries in <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>. `` National sovereignty is changing its whole meaning in European terms,'' says <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Hume </PERSON>, leader of the <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, the province's main Catholic nationalist party. `` The nation state is disappearing. So the fundamental reason for the quarrel between <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> is now gone.'' A backwater 20 years ago, <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> now has air links to European resorts. A burgeoning Catholic middle class hungers for stability. A retail boom has transformed the bombed-blackened city centers of <LOCATION> Belfast </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Londonderry </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Aidan </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Reilly </PERSON>'s family was driven out of their home in 1973 by <ORGANIZATION> Protestant </ORGANIZATION> mobs. Married now with a baby son, <PERSON> O'Reilly </PERSON> owns a house in a quiet <LOCATION> Belfast </LOCATION> suburb. He is one of the thousands who look back on the old days and pray they'll never return. By pouring some $ 2.25 billion a year into the province, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> can actually buy pockets of stability. Councilor <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> McGonnell </PERSON>, a 40-year-old schoolteacher, says <PERSON> Dungannon </PERSON>'s new approach is helped along by the knowledge that `` if a council is seen to be trying to work together, central government is much more sympathetic towards it.''
