<SECOND>BC-Walter Mears, Adv 06,0823</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv06</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Aug 6 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Washington Sights, Sites the Guidebooks Won't Tell You About</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: This stands for the regular column by Walter R. Mears, vacationing.</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE FEINSILBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 It is 9:45 on a Tuesday, Wednesday or Thursday morning and you are standing by the driveway outside the <ORGANIZATION> Rayburn </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Office Building. Up draws a limousine and out pour the chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Joint </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chiefs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Staff </ORGANIZATION> and a squad of briefcase-toting colonels. Here comes another and out comes the secretary of agriculture. Then the chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, the director of the <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION>, the surgeon general in starchy white. It is something to see, the arrival of officialdom at <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>' doorsteps to appear before committees and subcommittees, to ask, to explain, to defend, to dodge, to woo _ and to demonstrate that the checks and balances concept is alive and well in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> Officials arrive at other congressional buildings and the Capitol itself, but because all going to Rayburn use a single entrance, it is a fine place to behold the phenomenon. Tuesdays, Wednesdays or Thursdays are best, because those are <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>' three full workdays. Every town has a few places, people or phenomena that are uniquely its own _ just as the waltz of arriving officialdom is <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s alone. Here are a few other <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> institutions: _ The Billy Goat Trail It is a hiking trail on the <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> banks of the <LOCATION> Potomac </LOCATION>. If you think of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> as an effete city where no work gets done but words get spoken, the terrain's unexpected roughness, in such proximity to the city, will surprise you Why, one could fall off the trail and roll down the steep hillside into the rocks of the Potomac! No <ORGANIZATION> OSHA </ORGANIZATION> to come to the rescue. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Evangelidi </PERSON>, a hiking writer, says of the four-mile Billy Goat Trail: `` It is shaped by many elements of nature. At times it is inundated and scoured by rampaging floods of the <LOCATION> Potomac </LOCATION>. Its unusual flora barely survives in the hot, dry relentless summer suns and rocky geography.'' He suggests you watch out for snakes. There are places where you'll find yourself hiking on all fours, or grabbing hold of a wedge of rock. You might as well be in <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION>. _ Red Lion Row This is quintessential <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> architecture: the architecture of compromise. The owners wanted to tear down the late Federal and Greek Revival and Victorian houses along the 2000 block of <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Avenue </LOCATION>, four blocks west of the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, to make room for yet another block-long behemoth office building. Preservationists said no, those little houses are vital reminders of the scale and style of the city as it was when <PERSON> Lincoln </PERSON> paced the streets. A bargain was reached. The old two-story buildings were saved and converted to stores and offices; the behemoth rose attached to and behind them. The old houses, not just their facades, were retained; this was not just another face-saving gesture. Like most compromises, what results is not entirely satisfactory to everyone. _ <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Wade </PERSON> This entertainer came here about the same time <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> did but outlasted his fellow showman. <PERSON> Wade </PERSON> came from <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> to play the banjo and tell tall tales for a few weeks' run in a basement theater at at Arena Stage. <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, charmed, wo n't let him go A man of beguiling passion, <PERSON> Wade </PERSON> reminds people of their human commonality. He has revised his act, but the title of his first show best gives the flavor: `` Banjo Dancing, or the 48th Annual Squitters Mountain Song Dance Folklore Convention and Banjo Contest and How I Lost.'' _ <LOCATION> Rock </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION>'s Meadows Washingtonian <PERSON> Peggy </PERSON> <PERSON> Fleming </PERSON> is a citizen nature-lover who by dint of determination became a National Park Service ranger. Then she persuaded the authorities to stop mowing the grass in a few swatches of <LOCATION> Rock </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION>, which runs through the city. Controversy, as you can imagine, ensued. Some people think unmowed grass is mayhem, and even a park needs discipline, but <PERSON> Peggy </PERSON> <PERSON> Fleming </PERSON> prevailed. Twenty-three of the park's 3,000 acres were allowed to go wild. They are mowed once a year to keep them from becoming forests. The result: not lawn, not woods, but something in between. The next result: new flora and fauna that flourish only under such circumstances. Voila! Goldfinches, short-tailed shrews, purpletop grass, six-feet tall bull thistles, owls, the pearl crescent butterfly _ all thriving where they otherwise had n't and would n't. Like <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Wade </PERSON>'s banjo, <PERSON> Peggy </PERSON> <PERSON> Fleming </PERSON>'s Meadows are a <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> miracle, the unexpected pleasure; like the high-stepping colonels, the short-tailed shrews are a sight to behold.
</TEXT>
