<HEAD>$Adv13</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Aug. 13 or Thereafter ^Rising Nationalism Sparks
Anger Among Soviet Ethnic Groups</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: One of a three-story package on Soviet ethnic unrest.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Soviet-Georgia, b0669</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MARNEULI, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 `` We are not guests!'' says <PERSON> Achmed </PERSON> <PERSON> Ragimov </PERSON>, an Azerbaijani engineer in this city in the south of <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>. `` We feel this is our land.'' Georgians are equally vehement that the area around <LOCATION> Marneuli </LOCATION> is traditionally Georgian, and the dispute is not ancient history here. In June, five people died in ethnic violence in the district. Georgians claim they are gracious hosts who welcome refugees and bear no ill will to other ethnic groups. But they infuriate the Abkhazian, <LOCATION> Azerbaijani </LOCATION> and Turkish residents of <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> by insisting they are just guests. `` I certainly do n't feel like a guest,'' said <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Gasanov </PERSON>, who lives in a largely <LOCATION> Azerbaijani </LOCATION> area of <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> around <LOCATION> Marneuli </LOCATION>. `` My family has been here for 200 years.'' Growing Georgian demands for independence from the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> _ <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> is now a <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> republic _ have prompted the Azerbaijanis of the <LOCATION> Marneuli </LOCATION> area to call for secession from <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>. The population of the area is now three-quarters Azerbaijani due to the Moslem preference for large families. One summer night in <LOCATION> Marneuli </LOCATION>, an industrial city, a car full of youths careened about the town warning of an impending attack by Georgians. `` Several thousand men gathered, armed with axes, iron bars, clubs, and knives,'' said a local <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> official, T.G. Beridze. `` But nothing happened,'' said <PERSON> Anna </PERSON> <PERSON> Kleshnina </PERSON>, another party official. She added, however, that men carying green Islamic flags moved on to the nearby towns of <LOCATION> Bolnisi </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Dmanisiu </PERSON>, spreading the word: `` The Georgians are finished with <LOCATION> Marneuli </LOCATION> and now they are coming to get you.'' Fighting soon broke out, and the five deaths occurred there, she said. The 17-year-old <PERSON> Gasanov </PERSON> also blamed Georgian discrimination for his inability to find a job. <PERSON> Ragimov </PERSON> complained that Georgians commuting from <LOCATION> Tbilisi </LOCATION>, the republic's capital, are claiming all the local managerial jobs. Several older residents in the crowd that quickly gathered around a visiting correspondent insisted that the multi-national residents of <LOCATION> Marneuli </LOCATION> `` live together like brothers.'' `` I was born here, and I've never had any problems,'' said <PERSON> Farida </PERSON> <PERSON> Orudjeva </PERSON>. `` This land is Soviet. It's not his or mine.'' But that sentiment, which native Georgian <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> tried to instill by uprooting whole nationalities from their homelands, is proving to be rare among the myriad minorities of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>.
