<HEAD>Agreement Reached on S&amp;L Plan</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 11th graf, `With S&amp;L ...,' to CORRECT daily losses to $20
million sted $20 billion.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration and congressional negotiators reached agreement Thursday night on financing a sweeping $ 159 billion bailout of the savings and loan industry after <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republicans </ORGANIZATION> torpedoed a Democratic plan. The compromise was reached after a series of fast-paced developments in which President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> threatened to veto the bill, the Democratic-controlled <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> ignored him in on a 221-199 vote in favor of it and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION> fell six votes short of mustering the 60 needed to complete action. That automatically tossed the bill back into a <ORGANIZATION> House-Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> committee </ORGANIZATION>, which locked up the deal after 11 p.m.. Approval is expected by the full <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, and then the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, on Friday, the last day before the August colngressional vacation Treasury Secretary <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> and White House Budget Director <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Darman </PERSON> accepted a compromise proposal splitting the cost of the bailout so that only 40 percent of the $ 50 billion needed immediately would balloon the federal deficit. The deal calls for the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> to borrow $ 20 billion this year, raising the estimated deficit from $ 149 billion to $ 169 billion, and borrowing by a new agency to raise the $ 30 billion balance next year and the year after without counting that in the official deficit. `` Obviously we've only had an opportunity to make a quick review, but based on that review ... in the spirit of which the president sent us here, which was one of compromise, we accept,'' <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> said. The compromise was approved on a 26-22 vote among <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> members of the conference committee despite vehement objections from Rep. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON>, chairman of the tax-writing <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Means </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. Sen. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Sarbanes </PERSON>, D-Md., was the only one of the five <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> negotiators to vote against the deal All of the money would be used to close some 500 insolvent S & amp; Ls _ the bulk of them in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> _ and pay off savers whose federally insured deposits were lost through failed an often fraudulent loans. The administration and <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> had reached agreement long ago on the bulk of the legislation directing a massive overhaul of the industry's structure and regulation in an effort to prevent a recurrence of the cisis. But a confrontation over the financing which one Democrat characterized as a `` game of chicken'' had threatened to blow the deal apart. With S & amp; L losses mounting at a rate of $ 20 million to $ 30 million a day, both the administration and congressional leaders were adamant in their demands that the fix be approved before the vacation recess. `` Ninety percent of the people want to get out of here,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Moakley </PERSON>, D-Mass., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rules </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> `` They have reservations for vacation.'' <PERSON> Darman </PERSON> earlier had called the $ 20 billion - $ 30 billion, on-budget-off-budget split `` conceptually sound'' but declined to give it a blanket endorsement without a vote on it among the congressional negotiators Prior to Thursday night, the administration has steadfastly demanded that all of the bailout's costs be raised 30-year bonds issued outside the normal <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> borrowing process, and outside the official deficit. The bill also would institute a major overhaul of the government's regulation of the nation's nearly 3,000 thrifts and require their owners to put billions of dollars more of their own money at risk. `` Both of them are turkeys,'' Sen. <PERSON> Jake </PERSON> <PERSON> Garn </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Utah </LOCATION>, said of the alternative <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and Democratic plans for raising the bailout's costs `` It's a question of the lesser of two evils.'' Democrats contended <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s plan would increase the cost by $ 150 million a year over the next three decades because the bonds would carry higher interest rates than normal <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Treasury obligations. Rep. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Schumer </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.Y. </LOCATION>, described the dispute as `` politics, plain and simple.'' `` The only difference now is they -LRB- Republicans -RRB- do not want the deficit number to go up the first year of the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration,'' he said. `` If it did not cost any money to not tell the truth, that would be fine. But not telling the truth is going to cost $ 4.5 billion to $ 60 billion.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> issued his veto threat early in the day, shortly before the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> began debating the bill that has been months in the drafting. `` If the conference report is presented to me in its current form, I will veto the bill,'' he said. `` While Gramm-Rudman-Hollings is not perfect, it represents the only available institutional requirement for fiscal discipline by the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and the executive branch.'' Over the next 10 years, the costs, including interest, would rise to $ 159 billion, according to the latest administration estimates. The interest costs over future years push the three-decade total for the rescue to more than $ 285 billion _ $ 157 billion of it from taxpayers. S & amp; Ls would have to devote more of their lending to home mortgages. Their investments in risky real estate ventures would be curtailed and their purchases of junk bonds would be outlawed. It also would remove five decades of prohibitions on bank ownership of <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Ls, enabling banks to buy out their most competitive lending market rivals in many communities. A new government agency, the <ORGANIZATION> Resolution </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, would be established to dispose of between $ 100 billion and $ 400 billion in real estate and other property falling into the government's custody The property was used as collateral behind loans that defaulted when real estate markets _ particularly in the <LOCATION> Southwest </LOCATION> _ collapsed with declining oil prices, contributing to the failure of more than 200 S & amp; Ls last year alone.
