<SECOND>PM-Tax Forms,0490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Simpler Tax Forms Would Collect More Revenue, House Panel Told</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: also on general news wires.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX8</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An expert in cutting through gobbledygook is offering some free advice on how to cut the federal deficit and ease taxpayer anxieties: simplify federal tax forms. `` Further simplification of tax forms and instructions _ without compromising technical accuracy _ is possible,'' says <PERSON> Janice </PERSON> <PERSON> Redish </PERSON>, a linguist. `` The payoff would far exceed the investment.'' `` Such a project has the potential to collect billions of dollars in taxes that are not now paid and the potential to change the public's perception of the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> and of government in general,'' Ms. <PERSON> Redish </PERSON> said Thursday to the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Means </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee that oversees the <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revenue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. Ms. <PERSON> Redish </PERSON>, who recently wrote a `` user-friendly'' owner's manual for the <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Taurus </ORGANIZATION>, cited the basic 1040, the most common individual form, as visually overwhelming and incredibly crowded `` It has 65 numbered items _ and several unnumbered ones _ all on one piece of paper ... boxes on the left for some items and on the right for others. It means that <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> uses small type for most lines and then condenses that type even further to fit all the words in other lines,'' she said. She got no argument from the subcommittee. Chairman <PERSON> J.J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Pickle </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, had the Ways and Means hearing room decorated for the occasion with a copy of each of the 392 federal tax forms _ enough paper, he said, to produce a stack thicker than the District of <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> yellow pages. `` Do you need so many?'' <PERSON> Pickle </PERSON> asked a panel of <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> officials. `` I'm afraid so,'' replied <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Altman </PERSON>, who is in charge of the agency's tax forms coordinating committee. <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> Commissioner <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldberg </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> said that as a result of the big tax overhaul that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> enacted in 1986, the agency had to create 88 new forms and revise 162 others. `` So much for simplification,'' <PERSON> Pickle </PERSON> complained. `` Our tax forms and publications are often the first -LRB- and sometimes the only -RRB- contact taxpayers have with the service,'' <PERSON> Goldberg </PERSON> said. `` The <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> has no interest in making tax forms complicated.'' <PERSON> Goldberg </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> is constantly reviewing to determine how forms and publications can be simplified. In the works now, he said, are a simplified Form 1040A for older taxpayers, which will include new lines for retirement income, and a study to determine why only about one-quarter of the taxpayers who were eligible to shift from the long Form 1040 to a shorter form did so this year. Also, he said there will be a study that could lead to an overhaul of the W-2 form, on which wages are reported by employers, and new publications offering tax guidance for the military and for students.
