<FIRST>d f PM-FarmScene     08-04 0553</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Scene,0578</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Ships High Quality Grain Despite Drought</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: also on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GREENE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> says 1988 grain shipments from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> remained of high quality even though drought cut yields. The report by the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Grain </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inspection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, released Thursday, compared inspection records from 1988 and previous years for wheat, corn, soybeans and other grains. The report said wheat moisture decreased or remained the same for all lots, except hard red spring wheat. For hard red spring wheat, the average moisture was 11.9 percent, up from 11.8 percent in 1987. Wheat represented 36 percent of the total 115.7 million metric tons of grains and oilseeds exported in 1988. Nearly half the 42 million metric tons of exported wheat was hard red winter wheat; 19 percent white wheat; 15 percent hard red spring wheat; 14 percent soft winter wheat; 2 percent durum; and less than 1 percent mixed wheat. The report said corn moisture and the amount of damaged kernels decreased, but there was a small increase reported in broken corn and the presence of foreign material. Corn represented 40.7 percent of the total metric tons of grains and oilseeds exported in 1988. Except for a fraction, almost all was yellow corn. Soybeans showed an increase in test weight and a decrease in amount of damaged kernels, but an increase in the amount of foreign material and split soybeans. Soybeans accounted for 15.7 percent of total exports of grains and oilseeds in 1988, the report said. The other products are sorghum, barley, sunflower seeds, rye, flaxseed and oats.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> has issued its first permit for the use of genetically altered trees under the notion that what's sauce for the potato is sauce for the poplar. The department said the permit, announced last week, will enable investigators at <ORGANIZATION> Iowa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Ames </LOCATION> to study a natural plant defense mechanism that has been transferred from the potato. Twenty poplar trees, cloned for uniformity, will be tested to see if the defense mechanism is `` switched on'' when the trees are threatened by insects and other pests, thus saving plant energy when there is no threat. The genetically altered trees wo n't be allowed to bloom or produce seeds, <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> says.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Americans cut back on their fresh fruit consumption in 1988, the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> says. Per capita fruit consumption was estimated at 211.3 pounds in 1988, compared with the previous year's record of 214.3 pounds. `` Most of the decrease was attributed to reduced consumption of fresh fruit,'' the department said in its outlook and situation summary for fruit published this week.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> is offering help to food exporters take part in the premier trade show in the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> in February. More than 3,900 buyers and suppliers will attend the sixth <ORGANIZATION> Middle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> East </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Equipment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exhibition </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Manama </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Bahrain </LOCATION>, from Feb. 10-13. The department's foreign agriculture service can help with preparing exhibits, customs and labeling, as well as with hotel reservations and local transportation. Companies that want to exhibit should contact <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Condon </PERSON>, MEFEX'90 coordinator, High Value Products Division, FAS, <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION>, Room 4951-S, <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> DC </LOCATION> 20250-1000, Phone: -LRB- 202 -RRB- 475-3417.
