<HEAD>President: Savings Vital to Economic Growth</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAM ROSSIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTERREY, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Convincing Mexicans to keep their savings inside the country is essential for <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s economic recovery, says President <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Gortari </PERSON>. <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> inaugurated the <ORGANIZATION> Fifth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Meeting </ORGANIZATION> here Thursday with a plea to bankers to `` improve the quality of attention that customers receive.'' Increasing savings and providing credit to lower income groups `` is part of your responsibility,'' he told bankers. During the past few months Mexicans brought back $ 2.3 billion deposited in foreign banks, helping to boost the country's foreign reserves to $ 6 billion, said <PERSON> Miguel </PERSON> <PERSON> Mancera </PERSON>, general director of the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mexico </ORGANIZATION>, the country's central bank. <PERSON> Mancera </PERSON> told the nearly 1,500 banking and government officials from <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and other countries that the first half of 1989 saw an `` abundant repatriation, lured by high interest rates.'' It is estimated that Mexicans have $ 28 billion in foreign banks, mostly in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. To entice more people to bring back deposits, the government announced this week a plan to only minimally tax repatriated funds. `` We Mexicans must finance our own development. We can accomplish that by saving more and increasing income to the country through exports of manufactured products,'' <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Mancera </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s balance of payments showed a $ 585 million deficit through July, which he called `` relatively modest considering the circumstances.'' <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> paid out $ 600 million to service its public debt and $ 700 million on private debt service, he said. During the same period, <PERSON> Mancera </PERSON> said, net foreign direct investments totaled $ 900 million. The two-day meeting, held for the second consecutive year in this northern industrial capital, follows a July 23 accord between <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> and private bank creditors to restructure $ 54 billion of its $ 107 billion foreign debt.
