<SECOND>BC-Ticker Talk, Adv 07,0628</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv07</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Monday Aug. 7</HEAD>
<HEAD>Market Leaves Auto Stocks Behind</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 While many other stocks have reached or approached new highs of late, shares of the Big Three <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> auto manufacturers have faced trouble getting into gear. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, for example, traded late last week around $ 50, down from the peak of $ 56.75 it reached early this year. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, in the neighborhood of $ 24, is going for barely half its 1987 high of $ 48. And <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, even with a recent spurt from the low $ 40s to $ 45, remains short of its early-1989 high of $ 47.37. The group's laggard behavior is no puzzle to followers of the industry's fortunes. Car sales have been weak for some time now, and production plans have been cut repeatedly for the remainder of the year. Indeed, when Wall Street economists argue that the economy is headed for a recession, the state of the auto industry is usually one of the first pieces of evidence they cite. `` The weakness in the auto market has been quite obvious for months in disappointing car sales,'' said <PERSON> Kathleen </PERSON> <PERSON> Heaney </PERSON>, an analyst who follows the industry for <ORGANIZATION> Nikko </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` As a result, the earnings of the Big Three will begin to reflect the strain.'' Some observers say the industry is paying a price for the marketing innovations that helped sell so many cars from the mid-1980s through last year _ sales incentives such as rebates and cut-rate financing, and auto loans stretching out for periods as long as five years. When consumers go shopping to replace cars bought with four - or five-year loans, they often find themselves with little equity in them to use toward a down payment on a new vehicle `` Incentives are now the bane of every automaker selling cars in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Heaney </PERSON> says. `` Automakers have discovered that while they can no longer sell cars without some type of incentive, this year they are learning that they ca n't even sell cars with incentives.'' Those problems aside, many analysts argue that the industry was due for an inevitable down stage in its business cycle. The long-term trend is for growth of the American car and truck fleet at about 1.3 percent a year, the Value Line Investment Survey says in its latest quarterly report on the industry. From 1984 through 1988, the advisory service says, sales of vehicles surpassed that level, using up a lot of demand. `` We expect that unit sales comparisons will be negative through most of 1989,'' wrote <ORGANIZATION> Value </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Line </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Leach </PERSON>. All that does n't mean, however, that everyone on Wall Street is down on the auto stocks. `` Viewed from a long-term perspective,'' <PERSON> Leach </PERSON> said, `` industry fundamentals do n't look all that bad. `` The quality of domestically produced vehicles continues to rise and operating costs are being reduced, all of which should ultimately lift earnings.'' <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> Fricke </PERSON>, an analyst at <ORGANIZATION> Prudential-Bache </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION>, has just raised his ratings of the Big Three stocks. `` We think the stocks are already discounting a severe sales and earnings decline next year which we do n't think will happen,'' he said. `` The stocks tend to begin to outperform when the news background is bad, when interest rates have peaked and are headed down, and when a cyclical trough is in sight. Our call may be early, but we think the greater risk is missing the move up.'' Says <PERSON> Heaney </PERSON>: `` Although the outlook for the next year is not optimistic, we would be looking for an opportunity to buy these stocks.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon Aug 7</NOTE>
