<FIRST>a f BC-Buckwheat Adv07   08-04 0629</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Buckwheat, Adv 07,0651</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv07</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Monday, Aug. 7</HEAD>
<HEAD>Hoosier Finds Buckwheat a Hot Commodity Among Japanese</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BETH HARRIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> LeMaster </PERSON> has never visited <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, but this year 75 percent of his income will come from growing buckwheat used to make Japanese pasta. Through a contract with a Japanese trading association, <PERSON> LeMaster </PERSON> directs the processing and shipment of Midwest-grown buckwheat, including a crop from his own farm in <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>. He is one of a small group of American brokers with contracts to produce buckwheat for the Japanese. His one-year deal with the <ORGANIZATION> Buckwheat </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Millers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> to produce 22,000 acres in <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> will pay him $ 9 per 100 pounds. It's a growing business. Last year, just 25 percent of his income came from buckwheat production. The Japanese consume about 250,000 tons of buckwheat a year, mostly in the form of a noodle called soba, a staple in their diet. Soba is made from a mixture of 30 percent to 50 percent buckwheat flour and hard red wheat flour. `` They tell me buckwheat flour has more protein, it's a sweeter flour and gives it an added flavor,'' <PERSON> LeMaster </PERSON> said in an interview on his farm near <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION>, a rural community about 100 miles northeast of <LOCATION> Indianapolis </LOCATION>. <PERSON> LeMaster </PERSON> started growing buckwheat almost as an afterthought in 1981 when rain threatened to keep him from planting 600 acres of soybeans. `` I just thought we'd feed it to livestock if nothing else,'' he said. `` But we started marketing it to some flour mills.'' Buckwheat is an attractive crop to farmers because of its short growing time and ability to produce a better crop on poor soils, <PERSON> LeMaster </PERSON> said. Its white flowers bloom four to six weeks after planting in mid-July and the crop matures in about 10 weeks. A farmer's investment is typically $ 20 - $ 30 an acre, <PERSON> LeMaster </PERSON> `` We're not competing with any of the other crops,'' <PERSON> LeMaster </PERSON> said. `` Not only is it a profit to farmers, it enhances the soil the following year.'' As a protein source, nutritionists say, buckwheat is nearly unbeatable, and unlike other crops, it's mostly free of chemicals. Two-thirds of the buckwheat used in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> is produced in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, but the recent civil unrest there has caused the Japanese to search for alternate suppliers, <PERSON> LeMaster </PERSON> said. In <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, a large buckwheat producer, the government subsidizes freight costs, but the country's cold weather has hurt crops. `` The only reason we're getting it instead of them is because we have a lot less chance of losing a whole crop,'' <PERSON> LeMaster </PERSON> said. `` Down here, we're just about guaranteed of a crop every year. Since 1981, we've only had one year where we've had a total failure and we were delayed over 45 days at harvest.'' <PERSON> LeMaster </PERSON> expresses pride in his family run farm, which employs a handful of outsiders. A Rolex watch on his arm and a seldom-used pleasure boat in his yard are evidence of <PERSON> LeMaster </PERSON>'s success. He said he wants to see buckwheat qualify for the federal export enhancement program, which provides support to make certain crops more competitive in foreign markets. `` We can be more competitive in price, still maintain a good price to our farmers and we'd probably be looking at 80,000 acres through the Corn Belt region,'' he said. <PERSON> LeMaster </PERSON> said he's been working with representatives of the <ORGANIZATION> Buckwheat </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Millers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> and the other American brokers to arrange a meeting with <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Evan </PERSON> <PERSON> Bayh </PERSON> to discuss export enhancement and crop insurance. `` We tell all of our growers how important it is to keep the buckwheat clean and free from other grains because if we want their business we have to maintain a high standard of quality,'' he said. End adv for Monday Aug. 7
