<FIRST>u f AM-BrownSuitComeback Bjt   08-04 0678</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brown Suit Comeback, Bjt,0701</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brown Suits Are Staging A Minor Comeback, Minus Spats</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY8</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Call it the latest summer brownout. <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> suits are making a fresh appearance this year, minus the two-tone shoes and natty hats, spats and cravats that your grandfather wore with them. Clothiers say the modern brown suit is subtler than its ancestor and usually has a strong tinge of blue or gray, the official colors of the corporate office. About 5 percent of <ORGANIZATION> Hart </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Schaffner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Marx </PERSON>'s men's suits this year are in brown or olive shades and that share could double in 1990, according to <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bruno </PERSON>, executive vice president. Last year, <PERSON> Bruno </PERSON> said, sales were `` minuscule.'' Similar increases are being posted by <ORGANIZATION> Greif </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cos. </ORGANIZATION>, whose suit lines include <PERSON> Perry </PERSON> <PERSON> Ellis </PERSON> and Chaps by <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> Lauren </PERSON>, and <ORGANIZATION> Joseph </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Feiss </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, maker of Cricketeer suits. Theories for the trend range from the influence of European fashion to nostalgia for military uniforms to attempts by the clothing industry to drum up sales with a new look. Chocolate brown suits are still very out, despite a blip in sales after <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> wore them. What's in is taupe, a chameleon-like brownish gray that can range from pale to charcoal, from reddish to bluish to greenish. `` <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> is coming back,'' said <PERSON> Rick </PERSON> <PERSON> Pallack </PERSON>, a clothier to the stars in <LOCATION> Sherman </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Oaks </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, whose clients include talk show host <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> Sajak </PERSON>. `` Basically brown's never been an important color in this country. But taupe, with off shades of different colorations, that could be big, if the retailer gets behind it,'' said <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Bier </PERSON>, vice president of <ORGANIZATION> Greif </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cos </ORGANIZATION>. Clothing manufacturers are disarmingly frank about their attempts to engineer interest in browns and olives to increase sales. `` We're trying to stimulate the business by obsoleting last year's designs,'' said <PERSON> Bruno </PERSON>, of <ORGANIZATION> Hart </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Schaffner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Marx </PERSON>. <PERSON> Jeffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Moriber </PERSON> was spotted recently on <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION>'s fashionable 57th Street wearing a good-looking suit `` I would say it has a brown cast with blue influence,'' said <PERSON> Moriber </PERSON>, creative director of a public relations agency. `` I like it because it has a subtle pattern. It can go either way. It has blue tones as well as warm tones.'' Dressing advice books say a man in a brown suit wo n't be taken seriously, but taupe may be another matter. Its peculiar beauty is that no one can quite describe it. <PERSON> Webster </PERSON>'s Third New International Dictionary says taupe comes from the Latin talpa, for mole, and calls it `` a brownish gray that is paler and slightly yellower than chocolate, duller and slightly redder than mouse gray, and duller and slightly redder than castor.'' `` We started seeing it about five years ago,'' said <PERSON> Rick </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON>, a salesman at The Tailored Man in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>. `` It can have a green cast or an olive cast or a purple cast. ... It's hard to define.'' For fall and winter, taupe will carry on in its darker tones, as a thread or accent color in a pinstripe, windowpane or subtle plaid suit, said <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Julian </PERSON>, associate fashion director of the Men's <ORGANIZATION> Fashion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> Europeans have always used a bigger palette of colors in men's suits, and that influence is crossing the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> But the most interesting theory on the popularity of brown and olive is the military one. `` Men get a little leery of wearing things like taupes and olives when they just get out of the military. Right after World War II or the Korean conflict or the Vietnam War you could n't give away colors like that,'' said <PERSON> Sue </PERSON> <PERSON> Smyth </PERSON>, vice president for communications at <ORGANIZATION> Joseph </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Feiss </PERSON>. Now that the nation has been at peace for some time, the bad feelings are gone, she said. `` There may even be some nostalgia.'' Still, navy and gray are entrenched. `` You ca n't push a man that quickly,'' said <PERSON> Bier </PERSON> of <PERSON> Greif </PERSON> Cos. `` He's not in the same category as women. We only made that mistake once in our business and that's with the Nehru jacket.''
</TEXT>
