<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0557</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Sharply Higher On Employment Figures</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON-BC</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar rose nearly 2 percent Friday against major foreign currencies, its biggest gain in months, after a government report upset expectations of an economic slowdown. The dollar's rally was the mirror image of a debacle in the bond market. The selling binge in bonds drove interest yields higher and made the dollar-denominated securities more attractive to global investors. Gold prices fell in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trading after finishing higher overseas. The dollar remained well below the peaks reached in June in spite of its one-day surge, which amounted to 1.9 percent against the West German mark, British pound and Japanese yen and an even 2 percent vs. the Swiss franc. The <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> triggered the rally by announcing that nonfarm payrolls rose by 169,000 in July. Although the figure was consistent with economists' predictions, many traders had been betting that payroll growth would be much smaller. Also, the department revised upward the figure for June job growth. The job statistics renewed fears of inflation, which hurts the value of interest-paying securities. As a result bond prices fell and their yields shot up. The higher yields on bonds and short-term securities attracted money into dollars, said <PERSON> Marc </PERSON> <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON>, a vice president at <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION>. Also helping the dollar was heightened tension in the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON> said. The dollar widely is seen as a safe haven from political turmoil. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, the dollar closed at 138.05 yen, up 1.65 yen from Thursday. Later in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the dollar was quoted at 139.40 yen. In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> the dollar rose to 139.85 yen from 137.20 yen late Thursday. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the dollar jumped against the British pound, with sterling falling to $ 1.6150 from $ 1.6475 late Thursday. In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> the pound fell to $ 1.6060 from $ 1.6373. Other late dollar rates in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, compared with late Thursday's rates, included: 1.9070 West German marks, up from 1.8718; 1.6435 Swiss francs, up from 1.6115; 1.1783 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1733; 6.4555 French francs, up from 6.3395; and 1,370.50 Italian lire, up from 1,348.50. Other late dollar rates in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, compared with late Thursday, included: 1.8975 West German marks, up from 1.8650; 1.6353 Swiss francs, up from 1.6065; 6.4260 French francs, up from 6.3192; 2.1300 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0950; 1,366.00 Italian lire, up from 1,338.00, and 1.1775 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1715. In <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, gold closed at $ 372.86 a troy ounce, up $ 2.19 from Thursday. Gold rose in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> to a late bid of $ 370.75 a troy ounce, from $ 369.75 late Thursday. In <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, gold rose to close at a bid of $ 370.50 from $ 369.50 an ounce Thursday. On the Commodity Exchange in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, gold bullion for current delivery fell to $ 367.25 an ounce from $ 373.30. Later, <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> said gold was bid at $ 367.50, down from $ 372.25. Silver bullion prices held steady on the <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> market, where the metal was trading at a late bid of $ 5.23 a troy ounce, unchanged from Thursday. On <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s Comex, silver bullion for current delivery fell to $ 5.168 from $ 5.296 on Thursday.
