<HEAD>Younger Gallo Denied Re-Trial In Trademark Dispute With Brothers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FRESNO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The younger brother of winemaking giants <PERSON> Ernest </PERSON> and <PERSON> Julio </PERSON> <PERSON> Gallo </PERSON> has been denied a new trial in a trademark dispute that bars him from using the <PERSON> Gallo </PERSON> name to sell cheese. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Coyle </PERSON> ruled Friday that his association with a law firm that once represented the Gallo Winery is not a conflict of interest, and that there is insufficient evidence to warrant a new trial. The elder <PERSON> Gallos </PERSON> sued the brother they raised after he began using the family name to sell cheese in the mid 1980s. In his June 20 ruling, <PERSON> Coyle </PERSON> denied <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Gallo </PERSON> use of his full name as a trademark because consumers confused it with the famous E & amp; J Gallo Winery. The ruling allows <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Gallo </PERSON> to use his name as a signature or in block letters if the label contains a prominent trademark without the <PERSON> Gallo </PERSON> name. A lawyer for <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Gallo </PERSON>, <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Yanny </PERSON>, argued in the retrial motion that his client did n't get a fair trial because <PERSON> Coyle </PERSON>'s law firm represented <ORGANIZATION> Gallo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Winery </ORGANIZATION> in a 1983 trademark dispute with <PERSON> Gallo </PERSON> <PERSON> Salame </PERSON> of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Coyle </PERSON> wrote in the decision that lawyers representing <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Gallo </PERSON> knew of his association with the law firm, and had n't objected when he was assigned the <PERSON> Gallo </PERSON> cheese case <PERSON> Coyle </PERSON> said he does n't remember the earlier case, which was settled before he became a district judge. <PERSON> Yanny </PERSON> also argued that the original ruling denied <PERSON> Gallo </PERSON> his freedom of `` commercial speech'' as protected by the First Amendment. But <PERSON> Coyle </PERSON> ruled that those arguments had been covered in the trial.
