<HEAD>Commodities Probe Indictments to Multiply; Half Cooperate With Feds</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS last graf to CLARIFY that assets may be seized only if
they were obtained illegally. A version also moving on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHERI T. PRASSO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 There's no telling how many people will be indicted as a result of the ongoing federal probe into fraudulent trading at the world's largest futures exchanges, but it could be as many as 200, a defense lawyer said Friday. Attorney <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Collins </PERSON>, asked about a published report saying the next few months could bring an additional 100 indictments, said the government could seek many more than that _ or less. `` It could be as many as they want,'' said <PERSON> Collins </PERSON>, who represents an indicted trader. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Anton </PERSON> <PERSON> Valukas </PERSON>' office did not immediately return telephone calls, but his office has consistently declined comment about the breadth of the investigation into trading at the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. `` They could potentially indict anybody who ever put a -LRB- trading -RRB- jacket on'' said defense attorney <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Durkin </PERSON>, referring to minor violations. `` I think it will go on for a couple of years.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sun-Times </ORGANIZATION> reported in Friday's editions that more than 100 additional indictments are expected this fall, with charges ranging from minor infractions to major violations like those already charged. Meanwhile, 25 of the 46 traders indicted Wednesday were expected to cooperate with federal authorities in meetings next week, the <ORGANIZATION> Wall </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Street </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION> reported in Friday's editions. A handful of traders had been cooperating for months, and 14 have agreed to plead guilty and help investigators, federal sources have said. <PERSON> Collins </PERSON> said whether people decided to cooperate likely would be a matter of personal character, the strength of evidence against them, and whether they had information that was valuable to authorities. `` It's a matter of selling something valuable,'' <PERSON> Collins </PERSON> said. `` You've got to sell something to get something,'' he said. `` Some people as a matter of principle would n't even tell the truth to the government. Others would lie on their mothers to get out of it.'' <PERSON> Collins </PERSON> said his client, <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON> <PERSON> Ashman </PERSON>, would not cooperate. <PERSON> Ashman </PERSON> was indicted on one count of conspiracy under the federal Racketeer Influenced and Corrupt Organizations act, 13 counts of violating the Commodities Exchange Act and one count of making false statements to a government agent. The indictments capped a 2 -LCB- - year undercover investigation in which at least four <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> agents posed as traders at the two exchanges Pleas were scheduled Wednesday from 21 of those indicted before <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Marovich </PERSON>, who was assigned cases involving the Japanese yen pit. The 19 soybean-pit defendants were to be arraigned Aug. 25 before <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hart </PERSON>. Three more traders were indicted for alleged activities in the bond pit, and three others were accused of wrongdoing in the Swiss franc pit. In the indictments, traders were accused of systematically conspiring to skim profits from customer accounts and attempting to hide earnings from the <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revenue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. Brokers trading for their own accounts as well as customers' accounts, a practice called dual trading, were alleged to have routinely and illegally cheated customers with the cooperation of `` locals,'' or traders who traded only for their own accounts Eighteen of the defendants charged Wednesday are accused of violations of the RICO act, which carry penalties of up to 20 years in prison. RICO empowers the government to freeze defendants' assets before trial and to seize them upon conviction if they are found to have been acquired through illegal means. But the <ORGANIZATION> Sun-Times </ORGANIZATION> quoted government sources as saying prosecutors would not try to seize defendants' homes.
