<HEAD>Precious Metals Plunge On Dollar's Strength</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Gold and silver futures prices fell sharply Friday on <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> as the dollar surged in value against other major currencies in reaction to the government's report on July unemployment On other markets, the major agricultural commodities were higher while energy futures prices were mostly lower. Gold futures settled $ 5.40 to $ 6 lower with August at $ 367.80 a troy ounce; silver was 12.2 cents to 13.3 cents lower with September at $ 5.20 a troy ounce. The <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s report of a 5.2 percent jobless rate in July fell within the market's expectations and was considered neutral for the financial markets, analysts said. But the agency's revision of the June non-farm payroll number, showing a gain of 250,000 jobs instead of 180,000, indicated the economy was healthier than had previously been believed. `` That revision obviously pointed toward the fact that while the economy has slowed down significantly, it certainly is not pointing toward an imminent recession,'' said <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Cardillo </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Josephthal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` Either way, it means economic conditions do not favor metals,'' he said. `` They'll have to look to the dollar for direction.'' The dollar skyrocketed and interest rates jumped in response to the report, prompting a shift of investment dollars from the precious metals to interest-bearing instruments. Soybean futures prices posted strong gains on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION>, rebounding from a weeklong string of losses as traders evened up their positions ahead of the weekend. Grain futures also advanced, partly in tandem with soybeans and partly in reaction to a private crop-production estimate pegging the 1989 corn and soybean harvests slightly below <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> projections. Soybeans for delivery in August had fallen a total of more than 85 cents a bushel in the five previous sessions as growing conditions improved and supplies of newly harvested South American soybeans increased. `` This rally was long overdue,'' said <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Spilka </PERSON>, grain-market analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Smith </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Barney </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Harris </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Upham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` The market was oversold technically and it was just a matter of which day it would fall on.'' Wheat settled -RCB- cent lower to -RCB- cent higher with September at $ 3.87 -LCB- a bushel; corn was 1 -LCB- cents to 2 -LCB- cents higher with September at $ 2.19 -LCB- a bushel; oats were 4 cents to 4 -RCB- cents higher with September at $ 1.40 \ a bushel; soybeans were 6 cents to 16 -LCB- cents higher with August at $ 5.90 -RCB- a bushel Most live cattle futures climbed on buying spurred by strong cash markets. Higher cash hog prices supported the pork complex. Live cattle settled .20 cent to .62 cent higher with August at 74.17 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .10 cent to .43 cent higher with August at 84.50 cents a pound; live hogs were .28 cent to .90 cent higher with August at 46.80 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .65 cent to 1.28 cents higher with August at 26.27 cents a pound. Crude oil futures sank on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> but the near-month contract failed to pierce $ 18 a barrel. Traders said volume was extremely light in an uneventful session. West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 16 cents to 21 cents lower with September at $ 18.03 a barrel; heating oil was .11 cent lower to .06 cent higher with September at 49.18 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was .43 cent lower to .10 cent higher with September at 51.24 cents a gallon.
