<HEAD>Whitney Cuts Offer for Prime</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In the wake of three consecutive quarterly losses, <ORGANIZATION> Prime </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Computer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> on Friday reluctantly recommended that its shareholders accept a buyout by J.H. <ORGANIZATION> Whitney </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> for about $ 1.1 billion, $ 74 million less than <PERSON> Whitney </PERSON>'s previous offer. Prime's board of directors said the merger was still preferable to selling its minicomputer business to <ORGANIZATION> MAI </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Basic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Four </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Tustin </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, which has offered $ 525 million for the division. <PERSON> Whitney </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> venture capital firm, said it would pay $ 20 a share for Prime's outstanding common stock, down from its previous offer of $ 21.50 a share or about $ 1.2 billion. The reduction in <LOCATION> Whitney </LOCATION>'s offer was not as drastic as Wall Street had anticipated, and Prime's stock rose $ 1.12 -LCB- cents a share to close at $ 17.75 Friday on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. An arbitrageur, speaking on condition of anonymity, said <PERSON> Whitney </PERSON>'s original offer had been widely viewed as untenable, and the new offer was more realistic, raising traders' confidence that the deal would go through. `` The board of directors of Prime is very disappointed that J.H. <PERSON> Whitney </PERSON> and its financial sources have not completed the $ 21.50 per share offer ...,'' said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dunn </PERSON>, Prime's chairman. `` However, after review of all the alternatives, the board of directors believes that the revised J.H. <PERSON> Whitney </PERSON> offer is the best economic alternative available for Prime stockholders,'' <PERSON> Dunn </PERSON> said in a statement. Prime, which makes minicomputers and computer-aided design and manufacturing systems, turned a profit of $ 19 million on sales of $ 1.6 billion in 1988. But the cost of defending against a takeover and slow sales of minicomputers led to losses of $ 14.4 million in the final quarter of 1988, $ 5 million in the first quarter of this year and $ 19 million in the second quarter. <PERSON> Whitney </PERSON> emerged last month as a `` white knight,'' or friendly buyer, to save Prime from a hostile, $ 970 million bid by MAI Basic Four and its chairman, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> takeover specialist <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> LeBow </PERSON>. After Prime reported the most recent, $ 19 million loss last week, <ORGANIZATION> Whitney </ORGANIZATION> came under pressure from its main financing sources _ <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chemical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> _ to line up an additional $ 50 million of financing to ensure that it could ride out a period of continued losses. <PERSON> Whitney </PERSON> said Thursday it had been unable to obtain the additional financing at $ 21.50 per share and was entering negotiations with Prime to reduce the offer. The revised offer of $ 20 a share applies to Prime's 49.5 million outstanding common shares, which represent about 79 percent of the company's stock on a fully-diluted basis. <PERSON> Whitney </PERSON> has offered to exchange notes with a face value of $ 22 per share for the remaining 21 percent of Prime's shares. Securities analysts said those notes would trade at a substantial discount and estimated the total value of the deal at $ 17 to $ 18.50 a share, or $ 1.06 billion to $ 1.16 billion. Prime postponed its annual meeting from Aug. 9 to Aug. 24 to give stockholders time to consider the revised offer.
