<SECOND>AM-Unemployment, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0138,0752</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jobless Rate Falls; Inflation Concerns Fueled</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 21st graf, `The payroll ...,' to CORRECT data for black
teenagers. Also moved on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Civilian unemployment dipped a tick to 5.2 percent in July, the government said Friday. Analysts say the data should ease fears of an imminent recession but heighten concerns about inflation. Joblessness was down from 5.3 percent in June, with nonfarm businesses adding 169,000 jobs, the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said. At the same time, June's job growth was revised from 180,000 to 250,000, additional evidence that the economy continues to grow, though at a slower pace than last year. `` This suggests an economy that is clearly, clearly far from a recession,'' said <PERSON> Elliot </PERSON> <PERSON> Platt </PERSON>, senior vice president of <ORGANIZATION> Donaldson </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lufkin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Jenrette </PERSON>. `` Despite a lot of signs of economic weakness the labor market remains fairly strong.'' <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Boskin </PERSON>, chairman of the President's <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advisers </ORGANIZATION>, said the report was `` good news'' and `` suggests the economy is continuing to expand.'' While the job growth number provided encouraging news, analysts were wary over data showing significant upward pressure on wages _ a welcome development for workers but a sign of stubborn inflation as well. The <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said average hourly earnings rose 0.8 percent in July after increasing just 0.1 percent in the prior two months. `` That's a very, very powerful increase,'' said <PERSON> Platt </PERSON>. `` Ominous,'' was the way <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advisers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> chief economist <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> <PERSON> Sinai </PERSON> described the wage gains Both agreed that July's wage increase should give pause to the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, which of late has relaxed monetary policy in hopes of fueling enough new growth to avert a recession. `` There will be no more easing by the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> until after Labor Day.'' said <PERSON> Sinai </PERSON>. The government said the unemployment rate fell last month even though civilian employment declined by 82,000 people to 117.45 million. The rate fell because of a larger decline, of 146,000 people, in the labor force _ the number of people who have jobs or are seeking employment. The job growth again came predominantly in the service economy, which accounted for 140,000 of the 169,000 new positions. Within services, government employment was down by 25,000 jobs but retail trade added 52,000, wholesale trade 5,000, transportation and public utilities 23,000 and finance, insurance and real estate 11,000. Both business and health services posted modest gains, the government said. The goods-producing sector added 29,000 jobs, with gains in construction and manufacturing offset somewhat by declines in mining and the automobile industry. The 35,000 boost in construction jobs came at the same time that housing starts and home sales were rebounding. Manufacturing posted a modest gain of 3,000 positions after three consecutive monthly declines. Employment in the auto industry fell by 12,000 jobs last monh after a decline of 16,000 in June, a slump coinciding with sluggish car sales. Employment in mining was down 11,000, a figure heavily influenced by coal strikes in <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION> that have sparked wildcat actions in other coal-producing states. The government said the average workweek for production and nonsupervisory employees in private industry increased by 0.3 hours, to 34.9 hours. The factory work week held steady at 41 hours and overtime in July averaged 3.9 hours a week, up from 3.8 hours in June, the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said. The jump in earnings brought average hourly pay in the private sector to $ 9.70 on a seasonally adjusted basis, up from $ 9.62 in June. The payroll and wage data are taken from the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s monthly survey of businesses A separate household survey found few major shifts in unemployment among demographic groups, although joblessness among black teen-agers fell to 27.4 percent last month from 36.5 percent in June. The June total had been up from 32.4 percent in May. These were the July and June rates for other population groups: _ Adult white men, 3.8 percent, up from 3.7 _ Adult white women, 4.3 percent, up from 4.1 _ White teen-agers, 13.4 percent, up from 12.6 _ Adult black men, 9.3 percent, down from 9.4 _ Adult black women, 9.9 percent, down from 10.5 _ Hispanics, 9 percent, up fro 8.1 A separate calculation of unemployment that includes members of the armed services stationed in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> was unchanged at 5.2 percent.
</TEXT>
