<HEAD>Pan Am Reports $7.7 Million Second-Quarter Loss</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> on Friday reported it lost more money in the second quarter than it did in the same period last year. <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> reported a net loss of $ 7.7 million for the quarter, compared with a loss of $ 5 million in the same quarter last year. The nation's eighth-largest airline company said revenue of its main subsidiary, <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION>, continued to suffer from lower international traffic in the wake of the <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> crash over <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION> last December. The latest loss occurred despite `` aggressive pricing actions'' and some benefit from the strike affecting rival <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> said. The results for the latest quarter include a gain of $ 92.1 million on the sale of the company's <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> unit and expenses of $ 28.2 million stemming from its unsuccessful takeover bid for <ORGANIZATION> NWA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, the parent of rival <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>. Total revenue for the second quarter declined 1.7 percent to $ 909.4 million from $ 925.4 million a year earlier. Combined revenue from the <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shuttle </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION>, a commuter airline subsidiary, jumped 47.8 percent to $ 83.2 million from $ 56.3 million, partly offsetting the decline at <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION>. `` We are determined to stay on course with our efforts to restore <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION>'s competitive position despite these unfortunate setbacks,'' said Chairman <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Plaskett </PERSON>. `` While our bid -LRB- for <ORGANIZATION> NWA </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- was unsuccessful, we believe <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> presented the type of opportunity we will pursue aggressively in order to secure <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION>'s long-term future. Separately Friday, <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> investor <PERSON> Alfred </PERSON> <PERSON> Checchi </PERSON> signed the acquisition papers to complete his group's $ 3.65 billion buyout of <ORGANIZATION> NWA </ORGANIZATION>. For the first half of the year, <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION>'s net loss widened to $ 158.8 million from $ 88.4 million in the same period of 1988. First-half revenue slipped 2.7 percent to $ 1.64 billion from $ 1.69 billion a year earlier.
