<HEAD>SEC Accuses Two Investors Of Trying To Cheat 100 Brokerages</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday accused two investors of a scheme to defraud more than 100 brokerages, including <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Co.. <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Prudential-Bache </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION> In a civil lawsuit, the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> says the investors, Jury <PERSON> Matt </PERSON> <PERSON> Hansen </PERSON> and <PERSON> Fergus </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sloan </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, and their <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> brokerage firm, <ORGANIZATION> Fermat </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associates </ORGANIZATION>, committed fraud by buying millions of dolars worth of securities without having sufficient money to pay for them and selling them later the same day at a profit to cover their cost, <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> reported in Friday's editions. The illegal practice is known as `` free riding.'' The <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> also charges the <ORGANIZATION> Toronto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dominion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> violated federal banking regulations by providing the investors with credit although the two did not produce collateral. The bank was not charged with fraud. The <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> said the investors, through a partnership registered in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Graycliff </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> SA </ORGANIZATION>, opened an account at the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> branch of <ORGANIZATION> Toronto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dominion </ORGANIZATION>. The agency said the bank often covered the investors' checks overnight when the funds in the account were insufficient. The investors then opened 250 accounts at more than 100 brokerages, using 76 names, the suit charges. Since December 1984, the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> claims, the defendants used this `` web of accounts'' to buy and sell securities on the same day. The agency says the men earned more than $ 1 million through the scheme but left debts of $ 1.5 million at four brokerage houses at which they had steep losses: <ORGANIZATION> Steinberg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Lyman </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Universal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dominick </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Dominick </PERSON>. The <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> said it found no losses at any other brokerages. Calls to the investors' office were answered by someone who identified himself as a temporary employee and said he had know knowledge of the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> suit, the Times reported. A message left on <PERSON> Sloan </PERSON>'s answering machine was not returned, the newspaper said. <PERSON> Hansen </PERSON>'s home phone number is unlisted. <PERSON> Elliot </PERSON> <PERSON> Schnapp </PERSON>, a laywer representing the men, said he belived the charges were without merit. `` It appears to us that the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> is seeking to retroactively declare illegal a type of trading many investors and banks have engaged in for many years and not thought to be illegal,'' he told the Times. He also denied that the men left debts at the four brokerages. In response to an <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> request, a <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> judge in <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> on Thursday issued a temporary restraining order to stop the two men from continuing their investment activities. The court also froze their assets. In addition, the court issued a temporary order to restrain the <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION> bank from `` further violations of the credit extension provisions.'' In a statement, the bank said it had been cooperating with the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> for several months and was `` an innocent bystander in the areas under investigation.''
